 "[]", "order": 3}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 40}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "<p>MCRs (multicomponent reactions) are a valuable strategy in the &lsquo;green chemistry toolbox&rsquo; when designing a synthetic approach with sustainability in mind and are increasingly growing in application in medicinal chemistry and drug discovery programmes, combinatorial chemistry, natural product synthesis, and polymer chemistry.[bib]10.1039/C4GC00013G[/bib] They also are ideally suited for diversity oriented synthesis and library generation.&nbsp; In 2014 R. C. Cioc, E. Ruijter &amp; R. V. A. Orru published<a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1039/c4gc00013g\"> a review to promote the green process design opportunities available through the application of MCRs</a>.[bib]10.1039/C4GC00013G[/bib]&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 415, "modules": [34], "dirty": "[\"question_orders\"]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 41}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "", "remote_id": 463, "modules": [31], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 42}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "<p>Synthesis of organic molecules carrying a number of functionalities relies on the conversion of functional groups that display high reactivity, into the target functional groups. Carbon&ndash;hydrogen (C&ndash;H) bonds are not classically considered functional groups within the context of functionalisation. Therefore introduction of a new bond requires the presence of either a heteroatom on the carbon backbone, a leaving group or unsaturation.</p>", "remote_id": 450, "modules": [30], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 43}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "", "remote_id": 453, "modules": [27], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 44}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "", "remote_id": 475, "modules": [29], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 45}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "", "remote_id": 492, "modules": [12], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 46}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Case studies", "text": "", "remote_id": 493, "modules": [12], "dirty": "[]", "order": 3}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 47}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Introduction", "text": "", "remote_id": 524, "modules": [18], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 48}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Fundamental concepts", "text": "<p>Before we look more in depth at the new synthetic tools available to use whilst greening our reactions, we will explore the concept of route selection which is at the foundation of developing new products and processes.&nbsp; Selecting the optimal route to make your molecules can have a major impact on both the environmental impact of your route as well as the cost of goods.</p>", "remote_id": 547, "modules": [28], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 49}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Applications", "text": "", "remote_id": 551, "modules": [28], "dirty": "[]", "order": 2}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 50}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Why do we use solvents?", "text": "", "remote_id": 555, "modules": [39], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 51}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Issues surrounding solvent use", "text": "", "remote_id": 559, "modules": [39], "dirty": "[]", "order": 2}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 52}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Survey of solvent use", "text": "<p>The CHEM21 project conducted a survey of solvent usage for papers published in Organic Process Research &amp; Development over a 6 year period (from 1997&ndash;2012) looking at three particular solvent classes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>solvents of concern (dichloromethane, n-hexane, diisopropyl ether, 1,2- dimethoxyethane, 1,4-dioxane, diethyl ether, 1,2-dichloroethane, and chloroform)</li>\r\n<li>dipolar aprotic solvents</li>\r\n<li>neoteric solvents.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;(Ref D. Prat, J. Hayler, A. Wells,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2014, <strong>16</strong>, 4546)</p>\r\n<p>Key findings were that:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Approximately half of the instances for use of dipolar aprotic solvents were for nucleophilic substitution reactions (primarily SNAr and SN2 reactions).&nbsp; The paper makes suggestions of how the use of DMF/DMAc/NMP/DMSO in these reactions could be reduced.</li>\r\n<li>2-methyltetrahydrofuran was the only neoteric solvent that demonstrated a significant increase in its during the survey period.</li>\r\n<li>Although some solvents of concern are unfortunately still being employed, pleasingly on on greater than 100Kg scale the survey showed that there is a large reduction in the use of DMF, n-hexane, diisopropylether, DMAc, DMSO and &lsquo;the complete elimination of diethyl ether and dioxane&rsquo;</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": null, "modules": [], "dirty": "[\"id\", \"question_orders\"]", "order": 3}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 53}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Telescoping", "text": "", "remote_id": 563, "modules": [38], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 54}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Solvent recovery", "text": "", "remote_id": 565, "modules": [38], "dirty": "[]", "order": 2}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 55}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Alternative solvents", "text": "<p>As more solvents become restricted or are phased out due to regulatory constraints, the need for greener replacements is becoming increasingly important.</p>", "remote_id": 568, "modules": [38], "dirty": "[]", "order": 3}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 56}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Approaches to solvent replacement in synthetic chemistry", "text": "", "remote_id": 578, "modules": [38], "dirty": "[]", "order": 5}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 57}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "\"Cradle to grave\"", "text": "", "remote_id": 599, "modules": [40], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 58}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "\"Gate to grave\"", "text": "<p>Typically, &ldquo;cradle-to-gate&rdquo; (basic chemical feedstock&rsquo;s to API) or &ldquo;gate-to-gate&rdquo; (intermediates supplied by external suppliers to API) life cycle analysis looks at the sustainability aspects of manufacturing the API, as touched on in the previous lesson [TODO: link]. This lesson, and the rest of this topic, examines sustainability issues for pharmaceuticals downstream from the API &ndash; the so called &ldquo;gate-to-grave&rdquo; lifecycle. This builds on the synthesis of the API, looking at contributions from formulation, packaging, transport and very importantly, the ultimate fate of the actual API substance in the environment.</p>", "remote_id": 604, "modules": [40], "dirty": "[]", "order": 3}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 59}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Routes into the environment", "text": "", "remote_id": 584, "modules": [41], "dirty": "[]", "order": 1}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 60}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Absorption and decomposition pathways", "text": "", "remote_id": 590, "modules": [41], "dirty": "[]", "order": 2}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 61}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "Analysis of API fate", "text": "", "remote_id": 593, "modules": [41], "dirty": "[]", "order": 3}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 62}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "title": "New approaches", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "modules": [], "dirty": "[\"title\", \"id\", \"question_orders\"]", "order": 4}, "model": "repo.lesson", "pk": 63}, {"fields": {"order_dirty": true, "ti