xt": "<p>The following pdf files provide an example reaction and a series of questions for you to test your understanding.</p><ul><li><a href=\"/sites/default/files/Direct%20Amidation%20Part%202%20Question%20sheet.pdf\">Questions sheet</a>; accompanying&nbsp;<a href=\"/sites/default/files/Direct%20Amidation%20Part%202%20Data%20sheet.pdf\">data sheet</a></li><li><a href=\"/sites/default/files/Direct%20Amidation%20Part%202%20Answer%20sheet.pdf\">Answer sheet</a></li></ul>", "remote_id": 127, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 32}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [7], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Introduction", "text": null, "remote_id": 128, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 33}, {"fields": {"files": [1230], "lessons": [8], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Introduction", "text": null, "remote_id": 124, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 34}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [8], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Morpholine question", "text": "<p>To test your understanding, you can work through the exercise below using the <a href=\"http://www.rsc.org/suppdata/c5/gc/c5gc00340g/c5gc00340g1.xlsx\">CHEM21 metrics toolkit spreadsheet</a> and following data sheets :</p><ul><li><a href=\"/sites/default/files/Data%20sheet%20Method%201%20One%20pot%20synthesis%20of%20morpholines.pdf\">Morpholine example: Method 1 data</a></li><li><a href=\"/sites/default/files/Data%20sheet%20Method%202%20Copper%20triflate%20catalyst.pdf\">Morpholine example: Method 2 data</a></li></ul><p>When you have completed, compare your answers with the model answers below:</p><ul><li><a href=\"/sites/default/files/Morpholine%20Answers.pdf\">Morpholine example: model answers</a></li></ul><p><strong>Scroll down the pages of the PDF below to see all questions.</strong></p>", "remote_id": 117, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 35}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [8], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Toolkit interpretation", "text": null, "remote_id": 118, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 36}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [8], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Large scale example", "text": null, "remote_id": 119, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 37}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [9], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Returning to the original question ...", "text": "<p><span>Below, look at these</span><span> methods again (c.f. <a href=\"/node/130\" target=\"_blank\">lesson 1</a>) now we have the detail from the 1</span><span>st</span><span> pass metrics toolkit</span></p><p><span>Would you now change your mind about the greenest option?</span></p><p><span>There is not necessarily a right or wrong answer. &nbsp;But this example s</span><span>hows </span></p><ul><li><span>how it is important to have more information than just yield!</span></li><li><span></span><span>the need to balance/weigh up the different parameters</span></li></ul>", "remote_id": 129, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 38}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [9], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Conclusions", "text": "<ul><li><span>Assessing green credentials is not trivial: there is no \u201cthis is green\u201d/\u201cthis isn\u2019t\u201d answer</span></li><li><span>The ultimate goal is to work towards an optimum process</span></li><li><span>Gaining a holistic viewpoint allows a balance to be found</span></li><li><span>Use of metrics bridges the gap between discovery &nbsp;and larger scale/process chemistry by highlighting issues at an earlier stage</span></li></ul><p></p>", "remote_id": 192, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 39}, {"fields": {"files": [1221], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "Listen to Barry from the ACS GCI Round Table and Helen from GSK explain why guidance on solvent selection is needed.", "title": "The need for solvent selection guidance", "text": null, "remote_id": 19, "dirty": "[\"intro\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 8}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 40}, {"fields": {"files": [1223], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "Listen to Helen Sneddon from GSK describe the criteria used when selecting solvents.", "title": "Criteria for solvent selection", "text": null, "remote_id": 72, "dirty": "[\"intro\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 41}, {"fields": {"files": [1224], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "Denis Prat from Sanofi surveys the similarities and differences between different organisations&#039; approaches", "title": "In-house selection guides", "text": "<p>A large number of solvent selection guides are available in the literature and have been developed in-house by a number of pharmaceutical companies including <a href=\"http://www.rsc.org/suppdata/gc/c0/c0gc00918k/c0gc00918k.pdf\">GlaxoSmithKline</a>, Pfizer (who have also produced a <a href=\"http://www.idpmultimedia.com.au/greenchemweb/documents/GreenChemWeb_A4Poster_Solvents.pdf\">freely-available printable poster</a>), Sanofi and Astra Zeneca. [bib]10.1039/C0GC00918K[/bib] [bib]10.1039/B711717E[/bib] [bib]10.1021/op4002565[/bib]. The ACS GCI PR has also produced<a href=\"http://www.acs.org/content/dam/acsorg/greenchemistry/industriainnovation/roundtable/acs-gci-pr-solvent-selection-guide.pdf\"> an industry-wide solvent selection guide</a>, which is also available as a&nbsp;<a href=\"https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/green-solvents/id446670983\">free application for mobile phones</a>.&nbsp;</p><p>Although there are a number of solvents where strong correlations in classification exist between the different guides, there are a number of discrepancies (as analysed by Denis Prat of Sanofi, and presented at the CHEM21 Work Package 1 Workshop in Manchester; see below presentation). &nbsp; The varying needs and priorities of individual businesses will have direct influence over the exact rankings of solvents. &nbsp;The CHEM21 project has undertaken a survey of these guides to compile the data, analyse and understand the differences therein and have subsequently published a combined guide. [bib]10.1039/C4GC01149J[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 34, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 42}, {"fields": {"files": [1222], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "Helen talks us through the general GSK solvent selection guide", "title": "Example: GSK solvent selection guide", "text": null, "remote_id": 18, "dirty": "[\"intro\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 43}, {"fields": {"files": [1393], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "The CHEM21 solvent selection guide", "text": "<p>[To be supplied]</p>", "remote_id": 76, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"type\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 44}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "Helen from GSK describes guidance available for more specific types of reaction", "title": "Guidance for specific reaction types", "text": null, "remote_id": 20, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"intro\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 6}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 45}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Chromatography guides", "text": "<p><span>Amgen have created a <a href=\"http://www.rsc.org/suppdata/gc/c2/c2gc36064k/c2gc36064k.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">chromatography</a></span><span><a href=\"http://www.rsc.org/suppdata/gc/c2/c2gc36064k/c2gc36064k.pdf\"> guide</a> for selecting a solvent/eluent mix to replace DCM/</span><span>MeOH</span><span> mixtures [bib]10.1039/C2GC36064K[/bib]. &nbsp;</span></p><p><span>Derived from a screened set of drug-like molecules with a range of differing functionalities and physicochemical parameters, the charts allow solvents mixtures with similar eluting strengths to be identified.</span></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p></p><p><span>For further reading, the ACS GCI PR have published a highly recommended review article on sustainable chromatography [bib]10.1039/C4GC00615A[/bib].</span></p>", "remote_id": 75, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 7}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 46}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [11], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "GSK reagent selection guideszzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzz", "text": "", "remote_id": 31, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 47}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [11], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "GSK example: oxidation to aldehydes and ketones", "text": "", "remote_id": 32, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 48}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [11], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "GSK example: reductive amination", "text": "", "remote_id": 33, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 49}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [11], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "GSK acid and base selection guides", "text": "", "remote_id": 62, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 50}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [11], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Pfizer selection guide", "text": "", "remote_id": 63, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 51}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [12], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Question 1", "text": "", "remote_id": 42, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 52}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [12], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Question 2", "text": "", "remote_id": 43, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 53}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [17], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Green Chemistry", "text": "<p>Green Chemistry is quite well defined by the <a href=\"http://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/greenchemistry/what-is-green-chemistry/principles/12-principles-of-green-chemistry.html\">twelve principles of Anastas and Warner</a>. [bib]102[/bib] &nbsp;These principles focus mostly on how one should carry out chemical reactions and make chemical products, and describe the synthesis of chemicals in an environmentally preferable way.</p><p>[greenprinciple:show]</p><p><span>The Twelve Principles gained prominence in 1998 [bib][/bib] and don\u2019t fully reflect the modern way of thinking.&nbsp;</span>&nbsp;This is explored further in section 2, <a href=\"/node/90\">Twelve principles for the twenty-first century</a>.</p><p>Resources:</p><ul><li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/user/GreenChemUofT/videos\">Green Chemistry Initiative, University of Toronto: video series on the 12 principles</a>, written by students for students</li><li><a href=\"http://www.acs.org/content/acs/en/greenchemistry/what-is-green-chemistry/principles/12-principles-of-green-chemistry.html\">ACS GCI PR statement of the principles</a> with accompanying commentary from experts in each area</li></ul>", "remote_id": 99, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 54}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [17], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Green Engineering", "text": "<p><span>Green engineering can be defined as the design, commercialization and use of processes and products that are feasible and economical while minimizing generation of pollution at source, and risk to human health and the environment [bib]10.1021/es032633u[/bib].</span></p><p>[bib]10.1039/C2GC36900A[/bib]</p><p><span>Green engineering:</span></p><ul><li><span><span><span>uses the tools of recycling, process intensification and design optimization to maximize the efficiency of a process, and reduce its burdens on the environment.&nbsp;</span></span></span></li><li><span><span><span><span>evaluates the manufacturing process as a system and seeks to optimize its design, and in the truest sense, incorporates the concepts of life-cycle analysis and environmental economics into an appropriate evaluation of the overall environmental impact</span></span></span></span></li><li><span><span><span><span>requires the development of a set of metrics that appropriately evaluate the environmental parameters that we seek to control.</span>&nbsp;</span></span></span></li></ul>", "remote_id": 100, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 55}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [17], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Sustainable Design", "text": "<p><span>Sustainable design looks out even more broadly to try to understand the relationships between the manufacturing system and the ecosystem.</span></p><p><span>Sustainability:</span></p><ul><li><span><span><span>focuses on the triple bottom line: the integration of ecological integrity, societal responsibility, and economic viability</span></span></span></li><li><span><span><span><span>takes the broadest level systems approach, looking at the planet as the system of interest</span></span></span></span></li></ul><p><span>In order to optimize design at this scale, new ways of measuring human impacts on the environment will be required.</span></p>", "remote_id": 101, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 56}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "How the principles look today", "text": "", "remote_id": 95, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 57}, {"fields": {"files": [1227], "lessons": [18], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Misunderstandings of green chemistry", "text": "<p>It's helpful when learning about the foundations of modern green chemistry to look at some common misconceptions, and how chemists in the area are working to counteract them. &nbsp;In a 2012 article, James Clark [bib]105[/bib] has&nbsp; highlighted some of the ways in which the traditional principles have been misunderstood.</p><p>In this video, he focuses on biodegradability (principle 10: design for degradation), in particular its tension with newer recycling techniques (born out of principles 1 and 2), illustrating that a na\u00efve understanding of the twelve principles is not sufficient in modern green chemistry thinking.</p>", "remote_id": 96, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 58}, {"fields": {"files": [1225], "lessons": [19], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Economic cost", "text": "<p>[greenprinciple:show:1:2]</p>", "remote_id": 92, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 59}, {"fields": {"files": [1226], "lessons": [19], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Legislation", "text": "<p>[greenprinciple:show:3:4:5:12]</p>", "remote_id": 84, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 60}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [19], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Supply risk", "text": "<p><span>[greenprinciple:show:7]</span></p><p><span>In addition to substances becoming restricted or unavailable due to changes in legislation, they may also be at risk due to<strong> issues with supply</strong>.&nbsp;</span><span>While renewable carbon has been a hot topic since the 2000's, more recently that attention has been broadened to include other critical elements including phosphorus and many metals.</span></p><p><span><em>This area is studied further in the introductory module Critical Elements</em>.</span></p><p></p>", "remote_id": 97, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 61}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [19], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Public attitudes to renewability", "text": "<p><span>[greenprinciple:show:7]</span></p><p><span>S<span>hifts in public attitude</span>&nbsp;mean that there is increasing pressure especially from consumers on manufacturers to produce bio-derived chemicals as replacements for fossil resources and substances now considered to be hazardous to us or to the environment. &nbsp;</span><span>Vijayendran [bib]104[/bib] recently estimated that, by 2025, over 15 % of the $3 trillion global chemical market will be derived from bio-derived sources. &nbsp;</span><span>As we begin to move away from petrochemicals, the use of biomass as a chemical feedstock will become increasingly important.</span><span>&nbsp;</span></p><p><span><em>This area is studied further in the introductory module Renewable Resources.</em></span></p>", "remote_id": 98, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 62}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [20], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Overview and history", "text": "<p>The field of Green Chemistry has moved from pollution control in the 1980s to a more holistic approach in the late 1990s with the publication of the 12 principles of green chemistry [bib]102[/bib] to the present, which has seen an explosion in the number of publications claiming to be green [bib]10.1007/s10698-009-9079-4[/bib]. &nbsp;Answering the question as to whether a reaction is genuinely \u2018green\u2019 is not straightforward and requires an objective method of measuring its environmental impact.</p><p>In order to assess the greenness of a reaction, a number of \u2018green metrics\u2019 have been developed, which allow chemists to quantify and qualify the environmental impact of their reactions and assist with the comparison of different routes/methods. &nbsp;Early green metrics focussed largely on efficiencies in terms of mass inputs and outputs, but this has since expanded to incorporate a much more comprehensive and holistic approach. &nbsp;The following references provide an excellent overview of available green chemistry metrics:</p><p>[ibib]10.1039/B206169B[/ibib]</p><p>[ibib]10.1039/C1CS15215G[/ibib]</p><p></p>", "remote_id": 183, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 63}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [20], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "The CHEM21 toolkit", "text": "<p>The CHEM21 project has developed a unified metrics toolkit to comprehensively evaluate the sustainability of chemical and bio-chemical reactions based on a series of key parameters (see figure 1). Moving beyond the use of \u2018mass based metrics\u2019 alone, the Toolkit uses a blend of both qualitative and quantitative criteria to assess how green a reaction is, as well as considering factors both upstream and downstream of the reaction itself. This ensures a truly holistic approach.</p><p><span>The rationale behind the toolkit and the methodology employed is now available in an open access publication [bib]10.1039/C5GC00340G[/bib]</span><span>. As part of the background to this work CHEM21 performed a survey of available Green Chemistry metrics, which is accessible within the </span><a href=\"http://www.rsc.org/suppdata/c5/gc/c5gc00340g/c5gc00340g2.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">supplementary information</a><span> of this paper.</span></p><p><em>For further study of green metrics, see the topic 2 module&nbsp;<a href=\"/node/110\">Metrics</a>&nbsp;.</em></p>", "remote_id": 184, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 64}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [21], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Worldwide initiatives", "text": "", "remote_id": 108, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.quest