o-fareast-language:EN-US;}\r\n</style>\r\n<![endif]--><strong><a name=\"_Ref436215037\"></a>Scheme 1 </strong><a style=\"mso-comment-reference: LS_1; mso-comment-date: 20151209T0959;\"><strong>Common C-C coupling reactions used in the pharmaceutical industry</strong> <br />(Reproduced directly with permission of the Royal Society of Chemistry from Fairlamb, <span style=\"background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;\">2016[bib]396[/bib]</span></a><span style=\"mso-comment-continuation: 1;\">)</span></p>\r\n<p>The approach for the synthesis of new bonds via pre-functionalisation dictates the process of synthetic strategy; reactive sites are typically incorporated by a series of transformations and as a result the starting materials can be very different to the final product. &nbsp;Thus, the direct conversion of C&ndash;H bonds of organic compounds into desired functional groups without pre-activation represents a crucial field in green synthetic chemistry.[bib]10.1073/pnas.0804348105[/bib]&nbsp;Such transformations have the potential to provide clean and economic methods for the preparation of a wide variety of important chemicals directly from hydrocarbons. Moreover, with such tools in the synthetic chemist&rsquo;s arsenal, new opportunities could present themselves that would have a significant impact on synthetic strategy.[bib]10.1073/pnas.0804348105[/bib]&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The challenge to direct C&ndash;H functionalisation stems from the high bond dissociation energy of the C&ndash;H bonds of aromatics and olefins (H&ndash;C<sub>6</sub>H<sub>5</sub>: 460 kJ/mol; H<sub>3</sub>C&ndash;H: 439 kJ/mol).&nbsp;[bib]10.1021/ar000209h[/bib]&nbsp;As such cleavage of these bonds requires high temperatures, the presence of strong oxidants and acidic or basic additives.[bib]10.1021/ar000209h[/bib]&nbsp;Such methods are incompatible for application with a significant number of functional groups, thus limiting their applicability. Accordingly, C&ndash;H bond functionalisation has been a subject of vigorous research over the last 20 years, and more recently with respect to the development of methods that overcome the drawbacks highlighted.[bib]10.1039/C1CS15083A[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>Recent reviews on the developments in C&ndash;H activation have been published by Glorius <em>et al</em>.&nbsp;[bib]10.1039/C1CS15083A[/bib]&nbsp;and Chang <em>et al</em>.&nbsp;[bib]10.1039/C1CS15082K[/bib]&nbsp;as well as a specialised review on organocatalytic C&ndash;H activation by Pan.[bib]10.3762/bjoc.8.159[/bib].</p>\r\n<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\r\n  <o:AllowPNG/>\r\n </o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\r\n</xml><![endif]-->\r\n<p class=\"MsoCaption\" style=\"text-align: center;\" align=\"center\"><a name=\"_Ref436215037\"></a>Scheme <span style=\"mso-bookmark: _Ref436215037;\"><span style=\"mso-no-proof: yes;\">1</span></span> <a style=\"mso-comment-reference: LS_1; mso-comment-date: 20151209T0959;\">Common C-C coupling reactions used in the pharmaceutical industry (Reproduced directly from Fairlamb, <span style=\"background: yellow; mso-highlight: yellow;\">2016</span>[</a><span style=\"mso-comment-continuation: 1;\"><span style=\"mso-no-proof: yes;\">4</span></span><span style=\"mso-comment-continuation: 1;\">])</span><span class=\"MsoCommentReference\"><span style=\"font-size: 8.0pt; color: windowtext; font-weight: normal;\"><a id=\"_anchor_1\" class=\"msocomanchor\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\">[LS1]</a><span style=\"mso-special-character: comment;\">&nbsp;</span></span></span></p>\r\n<div style=\"mso-element: comment-list;\"><hr class=\"msocomoff\" align=\"left\" size=\"1\" width=\"33%\" />\r\n<div style=\"mso-element: comment;\">\r\n<div id=\"_com_1\" class=\"msocomtxt\"><span style=\"mso-comment-author: 'Louise Summerton';\"><a name=\"_msocom_1\"></a></span>\r\n<p class=\"MsoCommentText\"><span class=\"MsoCommentReference\"><span style=\"font-size: 8.0pt;\"><span style=\"mso-special-character: comment;\">&nbsp;<a c