gin-right:0cm;\r\n\tmso-para-margin-bottom:10.0pt;\r\n\tmso-para-margin-left:0cm;\r\n\tline-height:115%;\r\n\tmso-pagination:widow-orphan;\r\n\tfont-size:11.0pt;\r\n\tfont-family:\"Calibri\",\"sans-serif\";\r\n\tmso-ascii-font-family:Calibri;\r\n\tmso-ascii-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n\tmso-hansi-font-family:Calibri;\r\n\tmso-hansi-theme-font:minor-latin;\r\n\tmso-fareast-language:EN-US;}\r\n</style>\r\n<![endif]-->", "remote_id": 451, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 113}, {"fields": {"files": [1253], "lessons": [44], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Scarcity of metal catalysts", "text": "<p>Catalysis is one of the overarching principles of green chemistry that offers significant energy, environmental and economic savings. At present, 85% of chemical products worldwide, both bulk and fine chemicals are made <em>via</em> methods that use a metal catalyst; most of these processes use precious metals to perform the chemical transformation. However, the limited abundance of these metals poses a substantial threat to these industries, even for those metals that are forecast to last for another 100 years (Figure 1) have various associated issues, such as the uncertain stability of their price based on the current rates of extraction. Furthermore, geopolitical uncertainty in areas that currently mine these metals, as well as potential market manipulation to limit the amount exported, can cause global shortages on the international markets.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:247]</p>", "remote_id": 452, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 114}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [44], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Use in the pharmaceutical industry", "text": "<p>Within the pharmaceutical industry, precious metal based catalysts are predominantly used in cross\u2011coupling reactions, with 17% of the transformations catalysed by palladium [bib]10.1021/jm200187y[/bib] (please see <strong>introduction to C-H activation</strong>), other palladium catalysed transformations include hydrogenation/hydrogenolysis, Bn/CBz deprotection.</p>\r\n<p>Given the prevalence of the use of precious metals in the synthesis of important molecules, finding alternative methods is not clear cut; as there are associated issues with the required selectivity, and the use of a different method would require complete or partial redesign of large scale processes. Moreover, small changes in a production process for pharmaceutically relevant molecules would require reopening of the associated registration files, which would incur further costs. In addition to the issue of the scarcity and cost of precious metals, the ligands associated with them in a given method can be more expensive per mole than the metal itself, and there are no means for their recovery. [bib]375[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 454, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 115}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [44], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Cost and scarcity mitigation", "text": "<p>The industry has gone some way to mitigating the cost and scarcity of catalytic species based on rare metals, through the development of metal reclaiming processes. An alternative strategy to metal reclaiming processes is to shift away from the use of scarce metals to more earth abundant and cheaper base metal catalysts. The major advantages to the use of base metal catalysts, aside from the greater abundance and low cost, include the fact that base metals exhibit low toxicity and are also environmentally benign.[bib]375[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>The application of such metals in catalysis has crawled behind the huge advances made by precious metals however; there has been a renewed interest in the challenge in matching or outperforming the high activity and selectivity demonstrated by the platinum group metals, through investigating new ligands and reaction conditions that overcome the unpredictable nature of base metals.&nbsp; First row transition metals are known to readily undergo one electron oxidation state changes, partake in uncontrolled reactions with elemental oxygen and display facile ligand redistribution. In contrast, precious metal catalysis has established a plethora of predictable chemistries based on two electron changes between oxidation states. Base metals such as cobalt, copper, nickel, iron among others are some of the most earth abundant and the nearly limitless supply of iron allows its use on vast reaction scales such as those of the Haber&ndash;Bosch ammonia synthesis.[bib]10.1021/acs.accounts.5b00385[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>Cobalt, iron and nickel catalysts have been investigated in parallel with palladium catalysts for carbon-carbon bond formation and it has been found that when supported by the appropriate ligands, nickel and cobalt can enable efficient coupling reactions allowing the formal addition of carbon-hydrogen bonds in unsaturated systems.&nbsp;[bib]10.1021/acs.accounts.5b00385[/bib] Iminopyridine ligands have shown promise as privileged ligands in iron catalysis, and have been used in iron-catalysed methodologies for the production of olefin hydrogenation, carbon&ndash;carbon and carbon&ndash;hetroatom bond formation.</p>\r\n<p>There have been many recent developments in the use of base metal catalysis in the synthesis of pharmaceutically relevant intermediates, many of which can be found in the <em>Accounts of Chemical Research</em> special issue &ldquo;Earth Abundant Metals in Homogeneous Catalysis&rdquo;.</p>", "remote_id": 455, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 116}, {"fields": {"files": [1277], "lessons": [42], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Fluorinating agents", "text": "<p>Fluorinating agents are, by their inherent highly reactive nature, not generally regarded as green or sustainable due to associated hazards and toxicity issues.&nbsp; However modern alternatives are being developed alongside safer handling techniques that facilitate safer halogenation reactions, with minimal impact on the environment <strong>(ref Chapter 17 of ebook)</strong></p>\r\n<p>The table below provides a summary of the main advantages and disadvantages of various fluorinating agents.<strong> (ref Chapter 17 of ebook)</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p><strong>Fluorinating Agent</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p><strong>What is it used to fluorinate</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p><strong>Why is it green?</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Advantages</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p><strong>Why is it not green?</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Disadvantages</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Elemental Fluorine</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Carbonyl compounds</p>\r\n<p>Aromatics</p>\r\n<p>C-H bonds</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Excellent atom economy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Highly reactive, toxic</p>\r\n<p>Specialist handling needed</p>\r\n<p>Often generate HF byproducts</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>HF</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Halide Displacements (S<sub>N</sub>2)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Excellent atom economy</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Extremely corrosive and hazardous</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Fluoride Salts (e.g. KF, CsF)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Halide Displacements (S<sub>N</sub>2)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Safe and easy to handle</p>\r\n<p>Excellent atom economy</p>\r\n<p>Few by-products produced</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Very hygroscopic but often needs to be dry for good reactivity</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>N-F Reagents (e.g. Selectfluor, NFSI)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Carbonyl Compounds</p>\r\n<p>Aromatics</p>\r\n<p>Alkenes</p>\r\n<p>Thioethers</p>\r\n<p>Organometallic reagents (e.g. organotin)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Safe and easy to handle</p>\r\n<p>Low toxicity</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Derived from elemental fluorine</p>\r\n<p>Expensive</p>\r\n<p>Amine waste generated</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Ruppert Reagent (CF<sub>3</sub>SiMe<sub>3</sub>)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Carbonyl compounds (nucleophilic)</p>\r\n<p>Aromatics</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Safe and easy to handle</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Silicon-containing waste generated</p>\r\n<p>Expensive</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Electrophilic trifluoromethylation reagents (e.g. Togni)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Carbonyl compounds (electrophilic)</p>\r\n<p>Aromatics</p>\r\n<p>Alkenes</p>\r\n<p>Alcohols/sulfides</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Few other ways of doing many of these transformations</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Iodoarene waste generated</p>\r\n<p>Expensive</p>\r\n<p>Reports of explosions</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>DAST / SF<sub>4</sub></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Alcohol &rarr; CF</p>\r\n<p>Carbonyl &rarr; CF<sub>2</sub></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Few other ways of doing many of these transformations</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Corrosive</p>\r\n<p>Explosive byproducts at high temperatures</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Fluoroform (CHF<sub>3</sub>)</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Carbonyl compounds</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Using byproduct of Teflon production which otherwise needs to be disposed of</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Very potent greenhouse gas</p>\r\n<p>Normally incinerated producing H<sub>2</sub>O, CO<sub>2</sub>, HF</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Trifluoroacetate Salts</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>Aromatics</p>\r\n<p>Carbonyl compounds</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>CO<sub>2</sub> is only byproduct produced on decarboxylation</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"154\">\r\n<p>CO<sub>2</sub> is greenhouse gas</p>\r\n<p>Produced using corrosive HF</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>", "remote_id": 461, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 117}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [42], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Further reading", "text": "<p>On green and sustainable halogenation processes: <br />G. Pattison in [ibib]374[/ibib]</p>", "remote_id": 462, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 6}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 118}, {"fields": {"files": [1263], "lessons": [45], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Prevalence of the amide bond", "text": "<p>The amide bond is a ubiquitous functionality; occurring in natural products, polymers and pharmaceutical molecules. In publications by Carey <em>et al.[bib]10.1039/B602413K[/bib]</em> and Roughley <em>et al.[bib]10.1021/jm200187y[/bib]</em> investigating the most commonly used chemical transformations in industrial Research and Development (R&amp;D) departments (process and medicinal chemistry) at three large pharmaceutical companies, both included amide bond formation as one of the top ten transformations in these fields. It is therefore unsurprising that amide bonds feature in more than 25% of known pharmaceutical molecules. The top selling drug in 2008 atorvastatin (trade name Lipitor&reg;) with sales of $12.4 billion contains a single amide bond. Other important drug molecules that carry an amide bond include penicillin (antibiotic), paracetamol (analgesic) and chloramphenicol (broad-spectrum antibiotic), Figure 1.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:250]</p>", "remote_id": 472, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 119}, {"fields": {"files": [1264, 1265], "lessons": [45], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Condensation", "text": "<p>Amide bond formation between an acid and an amine are formally condensations. The related esterification reactions are governed by equilibrium however, the mixing of an amine with a carboxylic acid or an acid base reaction forms a stable salt. This means that amide bond formation between these reactants is thermodynamically disfavoured as the equilibrium lies on the side of hydrolysis rather than bond formation, Scheme 1.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:251]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Scheme 1: Amide bond formation by reaction of an amine with a carboxylic acid is thermodynamically disfavoured</strong></p>\r\n<p>The subsequent condensation of the salt to give the amide bond can be achieved at high reaction temperatures ~160-180 &deg;C, which is not only energy demanding but can be incompatible in the presence of other functionalities. These forcing reaction conditions have been circumvented by activating the carboxylic acid by using a good leaving group bound to the acyl group of the acid, allowing the necessary attack by the amine group, Scheme 2.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:252]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Scheme 2: Amide bond formation through activating of the acyl carbon</strong></p>\r\n<p></p>", "remote_id": 473, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 120}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [45], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Synthetic methods", "text": "<p>Given the importance of amide bonds there is a plethora of synthetic methods and strategies available for their synthesis. The most popular industrial methods for amide bond formation rely on the aforementioned acylation method which account for 16% of all reactions carried out by the pharmaceutical industry, a breakdown of these methods is shown in Table 1.[bib]10.1039/B602413K[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>Table 1: Breakdown of acylation methods for amide bond formation in the pharmaceutical industry[bib]10.1039/B602413K[/bib]</p>\r\n<div align=\"center\">\r\n<table border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Method</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Frequency (%)</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Acid Chloride</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">52</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Coupling reagent</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">21</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Mixed carbonic anhydrides</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">11</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Carbonyl Diimidazole</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">9</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Other</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"205\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">6</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n</div>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The use of acid chlorides is the most common method for amide bond formation in industry, and in the majority of cases, the procedure involves <em>in situ</em> generation of the acid chloride. Mixed carbonic anhydrides provide a cheap and readily scaled method for <em>N</em>-acylation.[bib]10.1039/B602413K[/bib] In recent years the use of carbonyl diimidazole (CDI) has grown in popularity, as it is moderately priced and also readily scaled and worked up, however its use is limited as CDI is a sensitiser and its use on large scale is costly.[bib]10.1039/B602413K[/bib]&nbsp; The use of acyl chlorides and mixed anhydrides is an economical approach to the synthesis of amides, however all of these acylation methods use stoichiometric quantities of coupling agents, which make them expensive, wasteful and inefficient.</p>\r\n<p>Amide bond formation using enzymatic catalysis circumvents the poor atom economy associated with coupling agents, as well as the potential hazards related with the use of non-aqueous media chemical approaches.&nbsp; Methods such as lipase-catalysed amidation of carboxylic acids and the hydrolysis of nitriles catalysed by nitrile hydrolases are clean, efficient and safe routes to the synthesis of primary amides. Equally, the use of peptidases and acylases circumvents the need for protection/deprotection steps, which has a positive impact on the mass intensity of the process.&nbsp; The use of enzyme catalysed amide bond formation has the advantage of operating under mild reaction conditions and their specificity leads to excellent regio- and stereoselectivity.&nbsp;&nbsp; Despite the progress made in the area of biocatalytic amide bond formation and some commercial success, enzyme catalysed amide synthesis still suffers from a narrow substrate specificity and material intensive isolation stages, which limit their application.[bib]10.1039/B703488C[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>In their survey of the reactions used by the pharmaceutical industry in the production of drug candidates, Carey <em>et al.</em><em><sup>1</sup></em> note that not a single catalytic method was used for the synthesis of amides.&nbsp; There is still a pressing need for scalable catalytic methodologies for the synthesis of amides that are atom efficient and avoid the production of waste; this has encouraged research into the efficient preparation of amide bonds. Details on recent developments in the synthesis of amide bonds can be found in reviews by Valeur and Bradley[bib]10.1039/B701677H[/bib], Montalbetti <em>et al</em>.[bib]http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.tet.2005.08.031[/bib] and Pattabiraman and Bode.[bib]470[/bib] A specialised review of metal\u2011catalysed approaches to amide bond formation was published by Allen and Williams[bib]10.1039/C0CS00196A[/bib], and a recent review on catalytic amide bond formation on non-activated amines and carboxylic acids has been published by Adolfsson and co-wrokers.[bib]10.1039/C3CS60345H[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 474, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 121}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [45], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Recommended reading", "text": "<p><strong>Recommended reading:</strong></p>\r\n<p>Farhana K. Ferdousi &amp; Andrew Whiting in [ibib]374[/ibib]</p>", "remote_id": 476, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 122}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [46], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Flask vs. Pipe vs. CSTR", "text": "<p>The flask is an integral piece of equipment to the synthetic organic or medicinal chemist at lab scale however, on large scale the flask is uneconomical. The bulk chemical, petrochemical and polymer industries all opt for the use of pipes as the reaction vessels of choice, allowing them continuous operation and enhanced control over reaction conditions. The pharmaceutical and fine chemical industries on the other hand, frequently use continuous stirred tank reactors (CSTRs) to perform their reactions.&nbsp; The reason for the disparity of approach between these industries is that in the pharmaceutical industry, process development occurs incrementally over a number of years beginning with milligram scale and increasing successively by several orders of magnitude up to a scale of tons, as required.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib]&nbsp; As such scale up in the pharmaceutical industry is carried out by gradual increase in the size of the reactor rather than performing a costly and time-inefficient redesign of a process.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 487, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 123}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [46], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Benefits of flow chemistry", "text": "<p>The aims of green chemistry and industry support one another when a process is considered for upscaling; it needs to be safe, generate minimal waste and be energy efficient. A fundamental approach to green chemistry for industrial application is to address such issues at the outset of the project, ideally at the reaction discovery stage. Flow chemistry is an enabling technology that fits well at the interface between reaction discovery and scale up; such reactors offer substantial improvements in the management of heat and mixing as well as scalability, energy efficiency, waste generation, operational safety, offer a wide range of reaction conditions and unique opportunities for catalyst supports, telescoping reactions among others.[bib]10.1039/C1GC16022B[/bib][bib]10.1002/tcr.201100041[/bib][bib]10.1002/cssc.201000271[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>The advantages in efficiency and sustainability that continuous flow offers are that it allows for efficient use of energy and time. Both aspects being directly related to reaction rate as a slow reaction would require more time for completion. The standard approach for speeding up a reaction is to increase its temperature, however batch reactors are limited to the boiling point of the reaction solvent/reagents, by comparison flow reactors lend themselves well to safe temperature and pressure manipulation beyond that of standard atmospheric conditions. Thus reactions carried out in flow are often faster than the corresponding batch reactions and offer improved energy, time and even space efficiency, as faster reactions will require smaller reactors.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib] Many green solvents such as acetone or methanol have low boiling points making them inapplicable for use in certain reactions; performing reactions at high pressure in a flow reactor allows for their safe use at high temperatures.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib]&nbsp; Supercritical fluids add an extra facet, as they are inaccessible in the absence of high temperature conditions, thus their applicability in flow reactors offers further advantages over batch reactors.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 488, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 124}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [46], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Catalysis", "text": "<p>Catalysis is an important aspect of green chemistry and there have been many efforts to develop supported catalysts for use on large scale. In small scale batch reactions, the catalyst, reagents, reactants and solvent are mixed together and stirred until reaction completion, after which the bulk liquid is separated by filtration, after which the catalyst is collected for re-use or disposal.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib] In continuous systems, the catalyst can be fixed in space over which the reaction mixture is allowed to flow, allowing the reaction and the separation steps to be combined into a single stage.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib] The catalyst remains in the reactor, allowing for ease of recycling; this system also allows the catalyst a longer lifetime as a result of the reduced exposure to the external environment.[bib]10.1039/C0GC00133C[/bib] As a result, reaction rates and catalyst turnover numbers are augmented through use of high catalyst concentrations and continuous recycling. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>An area of chemistry that has been difficult to implement on large scale pharmaceutical production is photochemistry; light has long been considered a valuable tool for performing synthetic reactions, it acts as a traceless agent facilitating the reaction without the production of further waste or the need for removal from the reaction mixture.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib][bib]10.1002/anie.201200223[/bib][bib]10.1039/B913880N[/bib]Though photochemistry has found application on industrial scale, its use is still uncommon in the pharmaceutical and fine chemicals industry; largely due to the use of batch reactors and the challenges associated with using photochemistry on a large scale, where the sheer volume of the reactor does not allow for complete light penetration.[bib]10.3762/bjoc.8.229[/bib][bib]10.1002/ceat.201200009[/bib] Flow chemistry allows better access to photochemistry as a tool at a range of scales using inexpensive equipment: &nbsp;the reaction mixture is pumped through a transparent tubing or transparent chip microreactor which is irradiated with a light source, the small diameter of the tubes allows for satisfactory light penetration, permitting all reaction molecules to be exposed to the same amount of heat and light. This comprehensive light exposure generally means that photochemical reactions run in flow tend to be orders of magnitude faster than their corresponding batch reactors.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 489, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 125}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [46], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Challenges", "text": "<p>One of the major challenges to the efficiency and sustainability of fine chemical and pharmaceutical industrial scale production is that the final product usually involves a multiple step synthesis with numerous work-up and purification steps required at each stage, which impact negatively on the material efficiency of the industry. Thus, approaches that circumvent or simplify these steps can have an enormous environmental impact on multi-step chemical syntheses; even here continuous flow reactors offer a great advantage as they are well suited for telescoping reactions and many methods have been developed to enable this.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib][bib]10.1039/C0SC00381F[/bib]&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Reaction scale-up usually requires costly re-optimisation reactions due to the change in mixing and heating properties, thus reactions that may have worked well on bench-scale batch reactions may require increased times, super-cooling, or may be impossible to carry out on large scale. Good reactions should be easily scaled without requiring re-optimisation, since a green reaction should be scalable by default.&nbsp; Again flow methods offer an advantage: the basic way to modify the total amount of product prepared in a continuous system is to change the length of time the reaction is run. <em>Ergo</em>, continuous flow processes allow facile alteration of the amount of product output without the need to modify the whole process or by running multiple batches, therefore meeting the green chemical engineering principle of running to meet needs.[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 490, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 126}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [46], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Summary", "text": "<p>In summary, flow chemistry offers a viable and in certain cases superior alternative to batch processes; offering increased safety, efficiency and scalability. The application of continuous flow methods on process scale has seen rapid take up in recent years, and the research communities have been developing these approaches further to expand their scope of application. &nbsp;Recent reviews on the developments in flow chemistry and more detailed information on their advantages over batch reactors can be found in reviews by Newman and Jensen[bib]10.1039/C3GC40374B[/bib], Wiles and Watts[bib]10.1039/C1GC16022B[/bib] and&nbsp; Ley[bib]10.1002/tcr.201100041[/bib].</p>", "remote_id": 491, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 6}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 127}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [48], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Benefits of biosynthetic approaches", "text": "<p>The biggest challenges to the production of fine chemicals on large scale include environmental pollution, toxic waste, and the increasing cost of prevention and clean-up of environmental waste. Compared with chemical synthesis, biosynthetic approaches can offer several advantages; enzymes generally operate under biologically relevant conditions such as ambient temperatures and pressures, aqueous media and neutral pHs. This enables an array of diverse enzymes to work concurrently in the same environment e.g. a cell, as such it becomes possible to assemble a multistep synthetic pathway for the <em>in vivo</em> production of a complex molecule from cheap and abundant materials. This is in great contrast to traditional chemical multistep syntheses which would require purification, recovery and further processing of intermediates <em>en route</em> to the final product.&nbsp;[bib]10.1038/embor.2013.178[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>These characteristics of biotransformation facilitate &ldquo;one-pot synthesis&rdquo;, which is a challenging approach in chemotransfomations. The use of biosynthesis would thus circumvent the need for energy intensive and harsh reaction conditions, toxic or caustic chemicals and would enable the reactions to be carried out in greener solvents.[bib]10.1038/embor.2013.178[/bib] Bioderived chemicals would also limit the greenhouse gas emissions and the cost through use of cheaper simpler starting materials such as CO<sub>2</sub>,CO, hydrogen and salts.[bib]496[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>Although the repertoire of products production by naturally occurring organisms is broad, it is still predefined by evolution as the organisms have adapted their biochemistries for survival in particular environments. Synthetic biology can be used to modify the biochemistries of these organisms and tailor their metabolic pathways towards the production of pharmaceutically relevant products or intermediates from simple molecules.[bib]10.1002/anie.201302195[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 521, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 128}, {"fields": {"files": [1272], "lessons": [48], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Fundamental concepts", "text": "<p>Synthetic biology has been subject to numerous definitions, however all of the available ones agree that synthetic biology is the study of applying the principles of engineering to biology for productive purposes: the use of synthetic biology tools to deliberately design and construct biological systems or their parts to serve a particular purpose. A key area in synthetic biology is the construction of living &ldquo;production plants&rdquo; for the manufacture of complex chemical compounds from simpler starting materials, other research areas include bioinformatics (using synthetic gene networks), synthetic genomics and genome minimisation as well as the biosaftey and societal aspects of synthetic biology among others.&nbsp;[bib]496[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>In synthetic biology, &ldquo;chassis&rdquo; cells &ndash;cells within which the desired metabolic pathways can be expressed&ndash; are considered living cells that possess a basic metabolic pathway to produce primary metabolites and are capable of essential chemical transformations such as the production of energy and co-factor regeneration. The chassis can thus be furnished with a desired function such as the ability to produce a chosen chemical compound; whether the compound is natural or non-natural does not hold a bearing on the process as long as the genetic information for driving its synthesis is available or can be designed. The chassis is endowed with the appropriate genetic system that consists of devices (eg different DNA vectors), made of different parts (eg promoters, terminators, ribosome binding sites), Figure 1.[bib]496[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:256]</p>\r\n<p align=\"center\">Figure 1 Parts, devices and systems - the make of a chassis cell (reproduced directly from Glieder, 2016[bib]496[/bib])</p>\r\n<p>The concept of a chassis cell and its genetic system given in Figure 1 is an overly simplified representation; even in the simplest unicellular life form, genetic and metabolic processes do not work independently but have complex interactions in the cellular environment. However, the modular approach for the systematic assembly of a more complex genetic system from the well-defined essential parts is useful and essential for a systematic approach, as such powerful strategies that link the constituent parts together in an ordered, parallel or combinatorial manner have been developed.[bib]10.1002/anie.201302195[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 522, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 129}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [48], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Applications", "text": "<p>This approach has already found its way into industrial scale production of a variety of important molecules such as the production of insulin from <em>E. coli </em>and more recently in the production of naturally occurring bio-products such as the plastic monomers succinic acid, lactic acid and <em>n</em>-butanol as a solvent and next generation biofuel.[bib]496[/bib] This area is still in its nascence, but as it begins to mature it has the potential to carry significant impact on the green credentials of the pharmaceutical and fine chemical industry. A review on recent developments in the field of synthetic biology in the pharmaceutical industry has &nbsp;been published by Breitling and Takano.[bib]http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.copbio.2015.02.004[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 523, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 130}, {"fields": {"files": [1273], "lessons": [40], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Formal stereoselective C-H amination", "text": "<p><strong>[TODO: references]</strong></p>\r\n<p>Stereoselective C-H amination is a very attractive strategy for the conversion of simple low cost chemical starting materials to high value chiral amine building blocks, and has therefore attracted much interest in organic chemistry. &alpha;-Methylbenzylamine is a substructure of many complex organic molecules. <sup>[1]</sup> Therefore, it can be a valuable intermediate in their synthesis.</p>\r\n<p>The most successful chemical strategies reported so far have involved intramolecular and transition-metal catalysed reactions<sup>[2]</sup> with a number of elegant methods using both chemical<sup>[3]</sup> and enzymatic<sup>[4]</sup> catalysts. A cascade of 2 enzymes was reported recently for the terminal amination of fatty acid methyl esters<sup>[5]</sup> employing a recombinant biosynthetic cascade in a whole cell system. Previous work had already shown that whole-cell biotransformation is able to produce chiral amine from secondary alcohol, albeit in low conversion of 3%.<sup>[6]</sup></p>\r\n<p>Given that natural biosynthetic cascades often suffer from limited substrate ranges, we were interested to generate a <em>de novo</em> biosynthetic multienzyme cascade that is guided in design and build by retrosynthetic considerations.<sup>[7]</sup> The target enzymes for the cascade were carefully chosen to be complementary in substrate recognition. By introducing the pathway into <em>Escherichia coli</em> we have generated a biocatalyst which converts ethylbenzenes <strong>1a-e</strong> to predominantly (R)-1-phenylethanamines <strong>4a-e</strong> respectively (figure 1) with conversions of up to 26% and ee values of 97.5%. Under the present reaction conditions, no additional co-factor except for the amine donor IPA and molecular oxygen was required. Our approach is the first fully enzymatic approach to generate chiral amines at the benzylic position from alkyls.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:258]</p>\r\n<p class=\"SchemeCaption\"><strong>Figure 1 </strong><strong>|</strong><em>E.coli</em> BL21(DE3) cells harbouring a self-sufficient P450 monooxygenase (Y96F)<sup>[8]</sup> which produces scalemic mixtures of alcohols with a general preference for the (<em>R</em>)-enantiomer,<sup>[9]</sup> (<em>R</em>)- and (<em>S</em>)-selective alcohol dehydrogenases (<em>Lb</em>RADH using NADP<sup>+</sup><sup>[10]</sup> and <em>Re</em>SADH using NAD<sup>+</sup> as co-factor<sup>[11]</sup>), and an w-transaminase (ATA117 requiring an amine donor and pyridoxal 5&rsquo;-phosphate (PLP)<sup>[12]</sup>) capable to convert 4-substituted ethylbenzenes <strong>1a-e </strong>into alcohols&nbsp; <strong>2a-e, </strong>ketones<strong> 3a-e </strong>andfinally amines<strong> 4a-e.</strong></p>\r\n<p class=\"P1withIndendation\">The flexible generic nature of the design of the cascade will allow for the easy substitution of individual enzymes with homologues or mutants and thereby provide a cassette based modular approach for the design and construction of alternative cascades for the enantioselective C-H amination of other substrates.</p>\r\n<p class=\"P1withIndendation\">&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 525, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 131}, {"fields": {"files": [1271], "lessons": [40], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Reductive amination", "text": "<p>Chiral amines are an important class of organic compounds that serve as key intermediates in the synthesis of a variety of biologically active molecules.[bib]10.1007/s11244-013-0184-1[/bib] The formation of C=N bonds by the condensation of carbonyls and amines, followed by reduction of the <em>in situ</em> formed imine represents the most straightforward strategy for the generation of chiral amines.</p>\r\n<p>Most work has focused on the transition metal-catalyzed asymmetric hydrogenation of imines and particular attention was paid to the reductive amination of carbonyl compounds with primary amines. Several reagents and combinations have been reported through the years with a predominant role being played by modified borohydride reagents.[bib]10.1002/adsc.200900719[/bib] Inspired by the biological system NAD(P)H, Hantzsch ester has been employed as a hydrogen donor in combination with chiral phosphoric acid for the enantioselective reductive amination of aliphatic ketones to furnish amines with excellent enantioselectivities.[bib]10.1002/anie.201001715[/bib][bib]516[/bib][bib]10.1002/anie.200503062[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>The application of biocatalysis is an important complement to chemical catalysis for chiral amine synthesis in water. Two main types of enzymes were investigated so far for the transformation of carbonyl groups into amines: amino acid dehydrogenases and w-transaminases. Researchers within CHEM21 have identified imine reductases[bib]10.1002/cbic.201402213[/bib] as biocatalyst for chemo- and stereoselective intermolecular reductive aminations. This novel imine reductase-catalyzed approach constitutes a direct method for the synthesis of valuable amines under mild reaction conditions.[bib]10.1002/cctc.201500764[/bib]</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:260]</p>\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Scheme 1: Classical and novel reductive amination </strong></p>\r\n<p>This approach represents a simple and complementary strategy for the generation of novel carbon nitrogen bonds in aqueous reaction media. These reactions proceed efficiently for a variety of carbonyl compounds and amine nucleophiles. Low amounts of the imine intermediate led to the formation of valuable amines in good yields and high selectivities. A highly chemo- and stereoselective imine reductase was applied in reductive aminations of a panel of carbonyls and amine nucleophiles to afford primary and secondary amine products in moderate to high yield as well as enantiomeric excess.[bib]10.1002/cctc.201500764[/bib]</p>", "remote_id": 526, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 132}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Hierarchy of green chemistry and engineering", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 133}, {"fields": {"files": [1281], "lessons": [49], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Hierarchy of green chemistry and engineering", "text": "", "remote_id": 544, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 134}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [49], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Issues on a small scale", "text": "<p>Within medicinal chemistry, the need to synthesise small amounts of a large number of analogues in a short time period can often lead to preference for tried and tested methodologies.&nbsp; This can be to the detriment of efficiency and often using reagents that would not be suitable for use on a larger scale due to, for example, safety issues.&nbsp; However green chemistry and medicinal chemistry are not mutually exclusive and adoption of green methodologies at an early stage in drug design provides the opportunity not only to reduce the environmental impact of small scale discovery research, but also to facilitate a smoother transition when promising candidates are scaled-up.</p>", "remote_id": 545, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 135}, {"fields": {"files": [1287], "lessons": [49], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Introduction to the SELECT criteria", "text": "<p>The biggest impact a chemist can have on the economic and environmental performance of a manufacturing process is in selecting the optimum synthetic route using the best available techniques/technologies at that moment in time.&nbsp; Route selection is a complex process, and synthetic routes can change during the development pipeline of an API, and post launch as part of life cycle management activity.&nbsp; 'Critical Assessment of Pharmaceutical Processes; A Rationale for Changing the Synthetic Route'&nbsp;[bib]10.1021/cr050982w[/bib] developed the widely adopted SELECT criteria.&nbsp; A manufacturing route could be improved/ changed to meet any or all of the SELECT criteria.&nbsp; </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>S &ndash; Safety &ndash; removal/minimization of hazardous reagents/solvents.</li>\r\n<li>E &ndash; Environmental &ndash; removal/minimization of reagents/solvents harmful to the environment.</li>\r\n<li>L &ndash; Legal &ndash; no infringement of existing intellectual property.</li>\r\n<li>E &ndash; Economics &ndash; minimise cost of goods.</li>\r\n<li>C &ndash; Control &ndash; Process must be under control, validated, consistent impurity profile.</li>\r\n<li>T &ndash; Throughput &ndash; maximized space time yield.</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 546, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 136}, {"fields": {"files": [1284], "lessons": [50], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "API route selection", "text": "", "remote_id": 548, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 137}, {"fields": {"files": [1285], "lessons": [50], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Strategy and technologies", "text": "", "remote_id": 549, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 138}, {"fields": {"files": [1286], "lessons": [50], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Tools for route selection", "text": "", "remote_id": 550, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 139}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [51], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvent usage in the pharmaceutical industry", "text": "", "remote_id": 552, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 140}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [51], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "What factors are taken into consideration when selecting a solvent? ", "text": "<p>In order to gain a greater understanding of what makes the &lsquo;best&rsquo; solvent for a given reaction, one must look deeper into the physicochemical properties of the solvent, as well as considering hazards (both human and environmental) as well as other considerations such as recoverability, renewability and any regulatory issues.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Selection of a green solvent is complex as the following constraints all need to be taken into consideration (D. Prat, J. Hayler, A. Wells,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2014, <strong>16</strong>, 4546.) and<cite> </cite>D. Prat, O. Pardigon, H.-W. Flemming, S. Letestu, V. Ducandas, P. Isnard, et al.,<em> Org. Process Res. Dev.</em>, 2013, <strong>17</strong>, 1517.) </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Chemical efficiency for the reaction (as well as downstream considerations of isolation/work-up etc.)</li>\r\n<li>Safety/stability (flammability, flash point, resistivity, energy of decomposition, risk of peroxides)</li>\r\n<li>Human health issues (acute, long-term and single target organ toxicity)</li>\r\n<li>Environment (biodegradability, ecotoxicity, solubility in water, volatility, odour, life cycle analysis)</li>\r\n<li>Quality (in the case of pharmaceuticals this is related to the risk of impurities in the drug substance)</li>\r\n<li>Industrial Constraints (such as boiling point, freezing temperature, density, recoverability/recyclability)</li>\r\n<li>Cost</li>\r\n<li>Compliance with legislation e.g. regulations such as REACh is impacting on the use of some hazardous solvents, for example dipolar aprotics</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 553, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 141}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Survey of solvent use", "text": "<p>The CHEM21 project conducted a survey of solvent usage for papers published in Organic Process Research &amp; Development over a 6 year period (from 1997&ndash;2012) looking at three particular solvent classes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>solvents of concern (dichloromethane, n-hexane, diisopropyl ether, 1,2- dimethoxyethane, 1,4-dioxane, diethyl ether, 1,2-dichloroethane, and chloroform)</li>\r\n<li>dipolar aprotic solvents</li>\r\n<li>neoteric solvents.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;(Ref D. Prat, J. Hayler, A. Wells,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2014, <strong>16</strong>, 4546)</p>\r\n<p>Key findings were that:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Approximately half of the instances for use of dipolar aprotic solvents were for nucleophilic substitution reactions (primarily SNAr and SN2 reactions).&nbsp; The paper makes suggestions of how the use of DMF/DMAc/NMP/DMSO in these reactions could be reduced.</li>\r\n<li>2-methyltetrahydrofuran was the only neoteric solvent that demonstrated a significant increase in its during the survey period.</li>\r\n<li>Although some solvents of concern are unfortunately still being employed, pleasingly on on greater than 100Kg scale the survey showed that there is a large reduction in the use of DMF, n-hexane, diisopropylether, DMAc, DMSO and &lsquo;the complete elimination of diethyl ether and dioxane&rsquo;</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 142}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [51], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Survey of solvent use", "text": "<p>The CHEM21 project conducted a survey of solvent usage for papers published in Organic Process Research &amp; Development over a 6 year period (from 1997&ndash;2012) looking at three particular solvent classes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>solvents of concern (dichloromethane, n-hexane, diisopropyl ether, 1,2- dimethoxyethane, 1,4-dioxane, diethyl ether, 1,2-dichloroethane, and chloroform)</li>\r\n<li>dipolar aprotic solvents</li>\r\n<li>neoteric solvents.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;(Ref D. Prat, J. Hayler, A. Wells,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2014, <strong>16</strong>, 4546)</p>\r\n<p>Key findings were that:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Approximately half of the instances for use of dipolar aprotic solvents were for nucleophilic substitution reactions (primarily SNAr and SN2 reactions).&nbsp; The paper makes suggestions of how the use of DMF/DMAc/NMP/DMSO in these reactions could be reduced.</li>\r\n<li>2-methyltetrahydrofuran was the only neoteric solvent that demonstrated a significant increase in its during the survey period.</li>\r\n<li>Although some solvents of concern are unfortunately still being employed, pleasingly on on greater than 100Kg scale the survey showed that there is a large reduction in the use of DMF, n-hexane, diisopropylether, DMAc, DMSO and &lsquo;the complete elimination of diethyl ether and dioxane&rsquo;</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 554, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 143}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [52], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Legislative drivers", "text": "", "remote_id": 556, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 144}, {"fields": {"files": [1304], "lessons": [52], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Case study: Chlorinated solvents ", "text": "", "remote_id": 557, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 145}, {"fields": {"files": [1302], "lessons": [52], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Case study: Dipolar aprotic solvents ", "text": "", "remote_id": 558, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 146}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [54], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Introduction", "text": "<p>To reduce volumes of solvent used, one simple suggestion is to look at the number and types of solvents used in a synthetic pathway to a target molecule. In a synthetic process, it is fairly typical that a number of different solvents are used &ndash; this causes additional burden (e.g. removing solvent at the end of each step). &nbsp;Counting the number of solvent swaps may identify opportunities where steps could be carried out in succession using the same solvent, without the need to isolate the product (telescoping reactions). (G. Assaf, G. Checksfield, D. Critcher, P. J. Dunn, S. Field, L. J. Harris, et al.,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2012, <strong>14</strong>, 123) ).&nbsp; (</p>\r\n<p>L. Summerton &amp; A. Constandinou in <em>Green and Sustainable Medicinal Chemistry. Methods, Tools and Strategies for the 21st Century Pharmaceutical Industry</em>, ed.&nbsp; L. Summerton, H. F. Sneddon, L. C. Jones and J. H. Clark, Royal Society of Chemistry, Cambridge, in press, Beyond mass based metrics: Evaluating the greenness of your reaction,4, pages</p>\r\n<p>Within the pharmaceutical industry there can be regulatory issues associated with telescoping due to the need to isolate intermediates in order to demonstrate control.<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\"></a></p>", "remote_id": 561, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 147}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [54], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Case studies", "text": "", "remote_id": 562, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 148}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [55], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "About solvent recovery", "text": "<p>Recycling and recovery of solvents is an important downstream issue that should be considered.&nbsp;&nbsp; Solvent recovery can have a positive effect on the environmental impact and hence the metrics of a given process. Studies have been carried out to determine whether solvent recovery is viable depending upon factors such as the energy required to achieve this. (<em>Green Chem</em>., <strong>2010</strong>, <em>12</em>, 1826) ETH Zurich has also developed an LCA based tool that allows the environmental impact of waste-solvent treatment to be quantified. (http://www.sust-chem.ethz.ch/tools/ecosolvent)</p>\r\n<p>The incineration of spent solvent as opposed to their recovery has been shown to considerably increase the life cycle impacts (C. Jim&eacute;nez-Gonz&aacute;lez, A. Curzons, D. C. Constable, V. Cunningham,<em> Int J LCA</em>, 2004, <strong>9</strong>, 114)).&nbsp; However this depends on the complexity of the production of the solvent itself and its boiling point, for solvents such as diethyl ether incineration is a more preferable option than distillation in terms of Total Cumulative Energy Demand (CED). (C. Capello, U. Fischer, K. Hungerbuhler,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2007, <strong>9</strong>, 927))</p>\r\n<p>Solvent recycling is not as straightforward in API manufacturing as in other industries due to &nbsp;regulatory approval<em>. </em>Where solvent recovery is deemed to be uneconomical, other options include down-cycling the solvent for example for heat recovery or use in other industrial applications.&nbsp; (1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; D. K. Leahy, J. L. Tucker, I. Mergelsberg, P. J. Dunn, M. E. Kopach, V. C. Purohit,<em> Org. Process Res. Dev.</em>, 2013, <strong>17</strong>, 1099)</p>\r\n<p>Other approaches could include solvent &lsquo;leasing&rsquo; whereby used solvent is collected by supplier and cleaned up for reuse.</p>", "remote_id": 564, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 149}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Alternative solvents", "text": "<p>As more solvents become restricted or are phased out due to regulatory constraints, the need for greener replacements is becoming increasingly important.</p>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 150}, {"fields": {"files": [1292], "lessons": [56], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Bio-derived solvents", "text": "<p>Just because a solvent is bio-derived, does not necessarily make it green.&nbsp; The CHEM21 project has developed a new solvent selection guide (<strong><em>Green Chem.</em></strong>, 2016, Advance Article, <strong>DOI:&nbsp;</strong>10.1039/C5GC01008J) to assess new bio-derivable solvents alongside traditional solvents. [TODO: Link to section 2]<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\"></a></p>\r\n<p>A consideration in the case of some bio-derived solvents is their greater viscosity and higher boiling points.&nbsp;&nbsp; This can lead to potential issues with recycling and recovery due to higher energy demands. ( C. P. Ashcroft, P. J. Dunn, J. D. Hayler, A. S. Wells,<em> Org. Process Res. Dev.</em>, 2015, <strong>19</strong>, 740)</p>\r\n<p>Recommended reading:</p>\r\n<p>J. H. Clark, A. J. Hunt, L. Moity, J. Sherwood in <em>Green and Sustainable Medicinal Chemistry. Methods, Tools and Strategies for the 21st Century Pharmaceutical Industry</em>, ed.&nbsp; L. Summerton, H. F. Sneddon, L. C. Jones and J. H. Clark, Royal Society of Chemistry, Cambridge, in press, Renewable Solvent Selection in Medicinal Chemistry,3, pages</p>", "remote_id": 566, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 151}, {"fields": {"files": [1293], "lessons": [56], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "CHEM21 Case Study", "text": "", "remote_id": 567, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 152}, {"fields": {"files": [1290], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Introduction", "text": "<p>Solvent replacement is not a straightforward process, and all replacements will have both advantages and disadvantages that should be taken into consideration when making a decision. &nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 569, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 153}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvent selection guides", "text": "<p>A number of solvent selection guides have been published with the purpose of promoting the uptake of more sustainable solvents.&nbsp; These guides give the user a quick method of identifying problematic solvents and subsequently recommending preferred alternatives.<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\"></a></p>\r\n<p>[TODO: Link to section 2]</p>", "remote_id": 570, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 154}, {"fields": {"files": [1291], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvent screening", "text": "<p>Design of Experiments (DoE) and Principal Component Analysis &nbsp;(PCA<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\"></a>) [TODO: Link to Topic 5] can be used as tools to identify solvents to screen, and assist in decision making when looking for replacement solvents. (Moseley, J. D.; Murray, P. M. J. Chem. Technol. Biotechnol. 2014, 89, 623&minus;632)</p>", "remote_id": 571, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 155}, {"fields": {"files": [1295], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvent-less reactions", "text": "", "remote_id": 572, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 156}, {"fields": {"files": [1296], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Aqueous reactions", "text": "", "remote_id": 573, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 157}, {"fields": {"files": [1297], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Carbon dioxide", "text": "", "remote_id": 574, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 6}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 158}, {"fields": {"files": [1298], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Ionic liquids", "text": "", "remote_id": 575, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 7}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 159}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [57], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Summary", "text": "", "remote_id": 576, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 9}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 160}, {"fields": {"files": [1306, 1320], "lessons": [58], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Drivers towards whole-process thinking", "text": "<p>When considering the sustainability impact of pharmaceuticals, LCA/LCI discussions are often dominated by the impact of chemical synthesis.&nbsp; However, the customers and stakeholders of the pharmaceutical industry &ndash; e.g. the UK National Health Service (NHS), Swedish Medicinal Products Agency &ndash; &nbsp;are keen to focus not only on the environmental impact of the synthesis of the API, but on the whole product process all the way to the finished product delivered to the patient. For example, the pie chart in <strong>figure 1 </strong>shows the carbon footprint breakdown of the NHS, where the greatest contributing division is procurement &ndash; the goods and services brought in. A more detailed breakdown (the bar chart in figure 1) indicates that pharmaceuticals are the major contributing factor.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:278]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 1: Breakdown of the NHS Carbon footprint by sector for 2012<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><strong>[1]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<p>The carbon footprint figures for the NHS in 2004 are shown in Figure 2. &nbsp;By comparing the figures of 2012 to those of 2004, the data suggests that over this time, the carbon contribution of pharmaceuticals has increased by ~20%. This is not as a result of less sustainable manufacturing but is due to the changes in population demographics. The increasing population and an increasing aged population results in a greater demand for services of such organisations. This poses a real dilemma in reducing total carbon footprint in the face of increasing patient numbers and demand (this is covered further under Regulatory &amp; Safety Issues [TODO: link]).</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:XX]</p>", "remote_id": 595, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"type\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 161}, {"fields": {"files": [1305], "lessons": [58], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Challenges in effecting change", "text": "<p>Clearly, one way to reduce carbon footprint is to ask suppliers of products and services to understand and reduce the carbon footprint of the products and services they provide. A barrier to this is cost; with the increase in demand and budget limitations, governments and healthcare providers are also looking to reduce or limit costs. These pricing policies are not only directed towards high volume generic medicines but also new innovative medicines, where the cost is deemed too high for the clinical benefits the patient will receive,&nbsp; despite a new medicine being given a marketing license by the relevant authority (which considers patient safety and efficacy, not cost). As a result, cost has had a significant influence on prescribing policy in recent years.<br />When submitted for marketing authorisation, all medicines need to have an environmental risk assessment (ERA &ndash; covered in more detail in the Regulatory and Safety Issues section- Sections 6-10). <br />Currently the ERA is directed towards end-of-life fate of the API in the environment &ndash; the route of manufacture is not considered. However, the ERA tends to be &lsquo;for information only&rsquo;, in fact according to the EU directive 2004/27/EC, it is not a criterion upon which a marketing license can be denied. The decision to allow a marketing license depends on the risk/benefit ratio of the medicine to the patient. At the time of writing, no new medicine has failed to get a marketing license due to an unfavourable ERA. For some years in Sweden, data from the ERA has been made available to payers and prescribers in their database (Fass.se).[1] At a high level, Fass.se was designed to promote the prescription of drugs with the lowest environmental fate impact (whilst ensuring that the clinical benefits are equal for the patient).<br />For many years, fate in the environment has dominated the LCI of pharmaceuticals, but with carbon footprint and concerns about poor manufacturing practices of suppliers outside of the EU, attitudes are changing and moving towards the development of various ways to reward and promote greener pharmaceutical manufacturing. There have also be efforts to lobby the EU to formalise the consideration of fate and manufacturing practice when considering a license for new pharmaceutical products.[2] Whilst LCI data might not impact on new/novel therapies, especially best in class or first in class (the highest current performance level in an industry, used as a standard or benchmark to be equalled or exceeded)[KP1] , it is being proposed as a measure by which products containing the same API (generic drugs, such as ibuprofen or paracetamol) can be differentiated (Figure 3).<br /><br />[TODO: [KP1]Is this two terms and two definitions for the same concept, or two separate terms and two separate definitions? If latter, split into two brackets after each term, or re-write bracket to: (respectively the highest current performance level in an industry, and used as a standard or benchmark to be equalled or exceeded)]<br /><br />[figure:show:277]<br /><br /><strong>Figure 3 The life cycle of a pharmaceutical product, including end of life and potential recycling [TODO: reference]</strong></p>", "remote_id": 596, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 162}, {"fields": {"files": [1308, 1309, 1310], "lessons": [58], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "LCA example 1: anti-inflammatory API", "text": "<p>In order to understand where carbon footprints and other LCI hotspots are, we can look at the LCA analysis from the API to the finished product.&nbsp; The first example is an anti-inflammatory API (data provided by CHEM21 member, structure not disclosed).<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\"></a>&nbsp; The breakdown of the product formulated as tablets in a simple blister pack is given in Figure 4 (Tools and assumptions given [TODO: link] in appendix). As can be seen, the API synthesis contribution dominates the carbon footprint. This is fairly atypical<a id=\"_anchor_2\" name=\"_msoanchor_2\" href=\"#_msocom_2\"></a>&nbsp; for an average pharmaceutical product, and reflects the current niche therapeutic area in which the API is used as well as the small production run of 20 tonnes per annum. The manufacturing route is dated and inefficient having been established over thirty years ago. The carbon impact of 354 kgCO<sub>2</sub>e tablet is very high compared to the average pharmaceutical product. Novartis analysis of cradle-to-grave LCA / supply chain carbon footprint reported an average of 10 kgCO<sub>2</sub>e (CO<sub>2</sub>e: carbon dioxide equivalents)<a id=\"_anchor_3\" name=\"_msoanchor_3\" href=\"#_msocom_3\"></a> for the annual patient dose of a typical pharmaceutical product.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> To contextualize, this figure of 10 kg CO<sub>2</sub>e per annual patient dose would equate to driving 77 miles in an average car.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a> In the UK, CO<sub>2</sub>e for food consumption ranges from 7.2 to 2.8 kg per person per day. Production of 1 kg of beef gives a carbon foot print of ~72 kgCO<sub>2</sub>e.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref3\" href=\"#_ftn3\">[3]</a></p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:279]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 4: Anti-inflammatory API carbon footprint &ndash; original route of manufacture</strong></p>\r\n<p>Redesigning to a more efficient synthetic route to the API gives the carbon footprint shown in Figure 5. This reduces the effective carbon contribution of the API to the tablet from 89% to 77%, but reduces the carbon footprint per tablet from 354 gCO<sub>2</sub> to 166 gCO<sub>2</sub>, thus the benefits of changing the synthetic route are significant with respect to the carbon footprint as a whole. Looking at the contribution of the rest of the secondary manufacturing process, the API still dominates due to the low total annual production. Typically economies of scale work in both primary (synthesis of main product) and secondary (formulation and packaging) manufacturing, but are more pronounced with API manufacture.</p>\r\n<p>[show:figure:280]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 5: Anti-inflammatory API carbon footprint - new route of manufacture</strong></p>\r\n<p>Modelling the process to a production scale of 200 tonnes per annum gives a picture that is more representative of pharmaceuticals produced in higher volumes, with only 48% of the carbon intensity being due to the API synthesis; the contributions of the other inputs in secondary manufacturing are now clearer and can be seen in Figure 6.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:281]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 6: Anti-inflammatory API carbon footprint modelled to 200 tonnes per annum of API</strong></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 597, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 163}, {"fields": {"files": [1311, 1312, 1313, 1314], "lessons": [58], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "LCA example 2: selective \u03b21\u2013blocker", "text": "<p>&nbsp;The second example is a selective &beta;<sub>1</sub>&ndash;blocker, prescribed for hypertension and other cardiovascular conditions. In 2011, this medicine was the 19<sup>th</sup> most commonly prescribed generic medicine, so is a large volume product.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; The data below was the output of an LCA study on secondary manufacturing and was supplied by an EFPIA member [TODO: need to reference this better] . The available data is presented in Figure 7 and is a more representative example of most bulk pharmaceutical products.</p>\r\n<p>[show:figure:282]<br />[show:figure:283]<br />[show:figure:284]<br />[show:figure:285]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 7 LCA analysis of a &beta;<sub>1</sub>&ndash;blocker production downstream from API</strong></p>", "remote_id": 598, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 164}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Secondary manufacturing", "text": "<p>It can be seen from the above examples that manufacturing of API and its raw materials contributes ~50% in in each of the areas of: global warming, acidification, photo-oxidant formation and eutrophication. There are therefore many opportunities both in API synthesis and secondary production to lower the overall life cycle impact of pharmaceutical products at point of use.</p>\r\n<p>In secondary manufacturing, a number of areas can be considered for reducing environmental impact:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Technology:Predictive science</li>\r\n<li>New formulations</li>\r\n<li>New packaging</li>\r\n<li>New analytical methodology</li>\r\n<li>More robust processes</li>\r\n<li>Flexible batch/ continuous processing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Environmental benefits</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reduced waste</li>\r\n<li>Reduced energy consumption</li>\r\n<li>Reduced emissions\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>During development or production</li>\r\n<li>From patient use</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Improved recycling\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Easier</li>\r\n<li>Less to do</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Sustainability</li>\r\n<li>Less solvent usage</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Detailed analysis of secondary manufacturing is beyond the scope of this module; however it is worth noting a couple of further areas.</p>\r\n<p>For photo-oxidant formation, tablet production is the main source due to high Volatile Organic Compound (VOC) emissions (ethanol) during coating operations. Most EU and US based pharmaceutical manufacturers quote VOC losses (fugitive solvent emissions to air) of between 1-2% of total solvents consumed (most report these figures in annual Corporate Responsibility or environmental reports). Some secondary pharmaceutical manufacturing plants in Asia and the Far East lose 80-100% of the VOC solvents they buy in to the atmosphere. While the solvents used in coating are normally regarded as benign, like ethanol, they can contribute to photochemical oxidant formation.</p>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"id\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 165}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Packaging", "text": "<p>Packaging is another area in which a reduction in the use of materials and moving to more sustainable packaging materials should be considered, Figure 8 below shows an example of excessive packaging use. The packaging is for a one month (28 day) supply of 1.25 mg (API dose) capsules of Ramipril, an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor used for lowering blood pressure. Also, the savings reported by Novartis by reducing secondary manufacturing impact are shown in Figure 9 [TODO: expand this to describe the key findings in the text!].</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:xx]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 8: 1.25 mg Ramipril packaging&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:xx]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 9: Some beneficial improvements reported by Novartis that were gained in focusing on reducing the impact of secondary manufacturing.</strong></p>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"title\", \"type\", \"intro\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"id\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 166}, {"fields": {"files": [1318], "lessons": [59], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Detecting pharmaceuticals in the environment (PIE)", "text": "<p>Over the past 30 years analytical instrumentation and methodology have advanced to a point where we are able to detect very low levels of non-natural contaminants in the environment. Increases in detection limits and sensitivity have been driven principally by the development of hyphenated techniques &ndash; LC-MS-MS and extractive concentration methodology such as solid phase extraction, which has enabled detection and quantitation down to nanograms per litre (ng L<sup>-1</sup>) levels and lower.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>With around 3000 pharmaceutical products in use worldwide (as well as veterinary products and illicit drugs), a large number of pharmaceutical residues have now been detected in a wide range of environmental matrices. These residues, mainly unchanged APIs but also sometimes degradation products, are principally being detected in water and sludge, but have also been found to be present in organisms like fish and plants. <a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref3\" href=\"#_ftn3\">[3]</a></sup></p>", "remote_id": 602, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 167}, {"fields": {"files": [1318], "lessons": [59], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Impact of PIE", "text": "<p>The ability to detect and quantify levels of pharmaceuticals in the environment (PIE) has led to an explosion of interest and scrutiny, as evidenced by the near exponential increase in the number of publications in this area from 1980 to the present day as shown in <strong>Figure 1</strong>. Whilst a number of these publications will be on topics like the manufacture and sustainability of pharmaceuticals, the vast majority are focused on the subject of PIE.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:289]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 1: Scifinder&trade; search for pharmaceutical and environmental key words (November 2014)</strong></p>\r\n<p>PIE has also attracted the attention of a large cross section of the stakeholders in the pharmaceutical industry ranging from the producers, regulators, academics, non-governmental organisations (NGO), pressure groups and healthcare providers. Several examples of PIE appearing in both the scientific literature and public media are given below for further reading. Of course it should be noted that as &lsquo;headlines&rsquo; are meant to sell newspapers and media articles, they may not be as objective or scientifically balanced as they could be.However, it is important to be aware of how these issues can be perceived, rightly or wrongly, in the public sphere as this can ultimately impact upon the reputation of a company with further knock-on effects (covered in more detail under Regulatory and Safety issues [TODO: link]).</p>", "remote_id": 603, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 168}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "\"Gate to grave\"", "text": "<p>Typically, &ldquo;cradle-to-gate&rdquo; (basic chemical feedstock&rsquo;s to API) or &ldquo;gate-to-gate&rdquo; (intermediates supplied by external suppliers to API) life cycle analysis looks at the sustainability aspects of manufacturing the API, as touched on in the previous lesson [TODO: link]. this lesson, and the rest of this topic, examines sustainability issues for pharmaceuticals downstream from the API &ndash; the so called &ldquo;gate-to-grave&rdquo; lifecycle. This builds on the synthesis of the API, looking at contributions from formulation, packaging, transport and very importantly, the ultimate fate of the actual API substance in the environment.</p>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"intro\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"type\", \"id\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 169}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [59], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Secondary manufacturing", "text": "<p>It can be seen from the examples in the previous lesson that manufacturing of API and its raw materials contributes ~50% in in each of the areas of: global warming, acidification, photo-oxidant formation and eutrophication. There are therefore many opportunities both in API synthesis and secondary production to lower the overall life cycle impact of pharmaceutical products at point of use.</p>\r\n<p>In secondary manufacturing, a number of areas can be considered for reducing environmental impact:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Technology:Predictive science</li>\r\n<li>New formulations</li>\r\n<li>New packaging</li>\r\n<li>New analytical methodology</li>\r\n<li>More robust processes</li>\r\n<li>Flexible batch/ continuous processing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><strong>Environmental benefits</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Reduced waste</li>\r\n<li>Reduced energy consumption</li>\r\n<li>Reduced emissions\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>During development or production</li>\r\n<li>From patient use</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Improved recycling\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Easier</li>\r\n<li>Less to do</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Sustainability</li>\r\n<li>Less solvent usage</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Detailed analysis of secondary manufacturing is beyond the scope of this module; however it is worth noting a couple of further areas.</p>\r\n<p>For photo-oxidant formation, tablet production is the main source due to high Volatile Organic Compound (VOC) emissions (ethanol) during coating operations. Most EU and US based pharmaceutical manufacturers quote VOC losses (fugitive solvent emissions to air) of between 1-2% of total solvents consumed (most report these figures in annual Corporate Responsibility or environmental reports).</p>\r\n<p>Some secondary pharmaceutical manufacturing plants in Asia and the Far East lose 80-100% of the VOC solvents they buy in to the atmosphere. While the solvents used in coating are normally regarded as benign, like ethanol, they can contribute to photochemical oxidant formation.</p>", "remote_id": 600, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 170}, {"fields": {"files": [1315, 1316, 1317], "lessons": [59], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Packaging", "text": "<p>Packaging is another area in which a reduction in the use of materials and moving to more sustainable packaging materials should be considered, Figure 8 below shows an example of excessive packaging use. The packaging is for a one month (28 day) supply of 1.25 mg (API dose) capsules of Ramipril, an angiotensin-converting enzyme (ACE) inhibitor used for lowering blood pressure. Also, the savings reported by Novartis by reducing secondary manufacturing impact are shown in Figure 9 [TODO: expand this to describe the key findings in the text!].</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:286]<br />[figure:show:287]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 8: 1.25 mg Ramipril packaging&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:288]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 9: Some beneficial improvements reported by Novartis that were gained in focusing on reducing the impact of secondary manufacturing.</strong></p>", "remote_id": 601, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 171}, {"fields": {"files": [1319], "lessons": [60], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Introduction", "text": "<p>There are three main routes by which pharmaceutical molecules enter the environment, which are shown in <strong>Figure 1:</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Through normal patient use</li>\r\n<li>Improper disposal of unwanted pharmaceuticals and related medical devices such as patches, implants etc. into land fill or water courses</li>\r\n<li>Point source pollution at sites of manufacture/formulation</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>A fourth route which is starting to become more prevalent (or at least better detected) is the Illegal or off-label use of pharmaceuticals resulting in accumulation in unintended species like plants and animals.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:290]</p>\r\n<h3>Definitions</h3>\r\n<p><strong>Point source pollution</strong></p>\r\n<p>Discharge, intentionally or otherwise, of manufacturing waste containing higher than permitted or safe concentrations of API&rsquo;s into water treatment plants or water courses from a single source.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a></sup></p>\r\n<p><strong>Illegal / off-label uses</strong></p>\r\n<p>Off-label uses refer to the permitted use of approved medications for other than their intended indications<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref3\" href=\"#_ftn3\">[3]</a> and, combined with illegal usage of drugs, can therefore often lead to the accumulation of API residues in the environment or living organisms where they should not be found. Of course, potential issues with pharmacologically active residues in the environment may also apply to illegal/recreational drugs which are out of the scope of this work.</p>", "remote_id": 581, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 172}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [60], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Normal human use", "text": "<p>After administration, the API maybe excreted unchanged in urine or faeces or metabolised to new chemical entities.&nbsp; These metabolites may or may not be pharmacologically active; an API may give a single metabolite or multiple metabolites that are then excreted.&nbsp; Metabolism usually proceeds via oxidation, reduction or hydrolysis and can be followed by secondary processes such as sulphate formation, glucuronidation etc. Almost all API&rsquo;s and associated metabolites have such a low vapour pressure that loss <em>via</em> the lungs or partition&nbsp; into the atmosphere after getting into water or soil is never observed as a major route into the environment. Thus after dosing, the drug and any metabolites are excreted and thus enter, in the main, into the sewage treatment system where used or directly into the environment if no sewage system is in place.</p>", "remote_id": 582, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 173}, {"fields": {"files": [1320], "lessons": [60], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Improper disposal", "text": "<p>Unwanted/unused pharmaceuticals are disposed of <em>via</em> direct flushing of tablets etc. into the municipal sewage system or putting tablets into municipal solid waste systems which are usually destined for land fill. Eventually APIs in land fill sites, may leech out and contaminate ground water, although if blister packed or in containers, these would have to degrade first. Other solids like syringes, implants and patches improperly disposed of in land fill could also lead to API contamination of ground water. Industrial waste containing API residues can also be illegally land filled or dumped into water courses to avoid costs associated with proper disposal routes (land fill tax, incineration). An example of the magnitude of unused/unwanted pharmaceuticals is shown for Sweden in 2011 in <strong>Figure 2</strong>.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\"></a></p>\r\n<p><strong><strong>[figure:show:291]</strong></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 2</strong> <strong>Tonnes of unused/unwanted pharmaceuticals by sector for Sweden in 201</strong>[TODO:??]</p>\r\n<p>Unused medicines arise from a wide range of factors: patients not completing the prescribed course due to improvement in the condition, failure to take due to undesirable side effects, out of date drugs, damaged packaging, and many others. It is debatable as to the extent of the escape of APIs into the environment <em>via</em> this route compared to normal patient use and point source pollution.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a></p>", "remote_id": 583, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 174}, {"fields": {"files": [1321, 1322, 1323], "lessons": [61], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Pharmaceutical release in context", "text": "<p>It should be noted that any potential issues with API residues in the environment are common to all xenobiotic (foreign to a living organism) materials released through human activities. Nature does not generally differentiate between API molecules and any other chemical classes. Due to biological activity exhibited by pharmaceuticals such as antibiotics, (oncology drugs in particular), and indeed&nbsp; some undesired activities like endocrine disruption, there has been some debate that pharmaceuticals&nbsp; should be&nbsp; considered as a high area of concern.</p>\r\n<p>However, as pointed out by Taylor <em>et al</em>.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> pharmaceuticals are a small subset of chemicals, and there are thousands of chemicals that have been/are emitted into the environment for which we have no data with respect to their environmental fate, let alone biological activity at the molecular level. Several classes of widely used industrial compounds (phthalates, alkoxy phenols) have been shown to have potent endocrine disrupting potential.</p>\r\n<p>Thus, a chemical that is not classed as an API/or having API-like activity, is not except from having some mechanism of potent biological activity. For example, nitroglycerine, Warfarin and dimethyl fumarate, initially sold respectively as an explosive, a rodenticide and a mould inhibitor have subsequently all been used as pharmaceuticals. To gain some perspective on the scale of release of chemicals into the environment, data for releases of chemicals into the environment in the USA between 2003 and 2013 is shown in <strong>Figure 1.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:292][figure:show:293]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><strong>Figure 1</strong> <strong>2013 TRI National Analysis: Releases of Chemicals</strong>[2]</strong></p>\r\n<p>In the Toxic Release Inventory (TRI), a &ldquo;release&rdquo; of a chemical generally refers to a chemical that is emitted to the air, discharged to water, or placed in some type of land disposal unit. A closer breakdown for individual industry sectors in 2013 is shown in <strong>Figure 2</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:294]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 2 Breakdown of chemical releases in the USA 2013<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><strong>[1]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<p>Pharmaceuticals are a subset of chemicals, but it should be noted that the above data would not include API release into the environment through patient use or improper disposal of unwanted pharmaceuticals. Since TRI focuses on releases from industrial facilities, these figures illustrate that contamination of the environment by chemicals comes from many sources and not just the manufacture and use of pharmaceuticals.</p>", "remote_id": 585, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 175}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [61], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Possible pharmaceutical fates", "text": "<p>Pharmaceuticals are a subset of chemicals, but it should be noted that the above data would not include API release into the environment through patient use or improper disposal of unwanted pharmaceuticals. Since TRI focuses on releases from industrial facilities, these figures illustrate that contamination of the environment by chemicals comes from many sources and not just the manufacture and use of pharmaceuticals.</p>\r\n<p>Once released into the environment, an API or metabolite may be:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Decomposed to innocuous fragments and eventually mineralised &ndash; converted to carbon dioxide, nitrates, sulphates etc.</li>\r\n<li>Decomposed to more recalcitrant fragments that are persistent.</li>\r\n<li>Recalcitrant &ndash; does not decompose- and may or may not show undesirable biological activity.</li>\r\n<li>Bind to organic solids such as soils, river/lake sediments and sludge in sewage treatment plants where it could accumulate or slowly decompose. This binding rapidly reduces the concentration of the API in solution, but may not necessarily remove it from the environment. The extent (efficiency) of binding is dependent on the nature of the solid and thus will be location dependant.</li>\r\n<li>Loss to air is almost never seen for most APIs.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Therefore the two main environments are water (major) and land (minor).</p>", "remote_id": 586, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 176}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [61], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Release to water", "text": "<p>Judgements on a chemical substance related to releases to water are based on three main properties &ndash; Persistence, Bioaccumulation &amp; Toxicity (PBT). Any one of these properties may cause a problem, and they are often interactive:&nbsp; two bad properties together may cause significant problems. If all three properties are bad then the substance is probably already regulated if a solvent or chemical, but not necessarily an API.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Persistence (P) &ndash; the compound is recalcitrant and not biodegraded hence will persist in the environment.&nbsp; Persistence is now considered a problem <em>per se.</em></li>\r\n<li>Bioaccumulation (B) &ndash; concentration of materials from water into organisms &ndash; usually in lipids/fats. This property is very difficult and expensive to measure <em>in vivo</em> and usually the octanol/water partition coefficient (K<sub>ow</sub>) is used as a surrogate indicator of bioaccumulation.</li>\r\n<li>Toxicity (T) &ndash; kills or is deleterious to microorganisms/animals. It is worth noting, however, that Endocrine Disruptor (ED) issues are more complicated: toxicity can depend on organism life stage, e.g. infancy vs adulthood. Additionally, toxicity may be indirect, for example: Triggering changes in DNA leading to mutation or the development of enzymes that inactivate antibiotics thereby, whilst not harming the organism directly, can make it more prone to infection or disease.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These properties will be discussed later in the Regulatory and Safety Issues section [TODO: link].</p>", "remote_id": 587, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 177}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [62], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Techniques in use", "text": "<p>Typically, &nbsp;the information on the concentration, distribution and fate of the API in most regulatory ecotoxicity testing experiments used for the required environmental risk assessment (ERA) is determined using quantitative analytical techniques such as&nbsp; LC, LC-MS and use of a <sup>14</sup>C radio labelled API sample with the rate and extent of mineralisation being determined by measuring the evolution of <sup>14</sup>CO<sub>2</sub>. Structures of decomposition products are not normally determined, though many other studies are run and published where decomposition products are semi-quantitated by LC, and punitive structures proposed by LC-MS and LC-MS/MS.<sup>2</sup> It is rare for breakdown products to be isolated and subject to further rigorous structure determination such as NMR Spectroscopy and X-ray Crystallography.</p>\r\n<p>In most cases, the structures are likely to be correct, but caution should be exercised; especially with more complex molecules; as it is rare to see structures of degradation products that have been assigned by spectroscopy, to be validated by independent synthesis of standard materials. The lack of authentic analytical standards also means that many studies on transformation products are not properly quantified. Most studies that investigate the structure of degradation products are run in labs, and thus the decomposition compounds are rarely extracted from environmental samples.</p>\r\n<p>Typically photochemical degradation/oxidation, active sewage sludge, tests with microorganisms etc. are run in labs under conditions that mimic specific environmental conditions and therefore may not reflect the true decomposition pathway in the environment. Occasionally degradation studies are run in water-solvent mixtures or at pH values that would never be reached in the environment. We need to bear in mind that collections of degrading organisms like sewage sludge can vary in composition and activity subject to the location of sampling, time of year and other factors.</p>", "remote_id": 591, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 178}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [61], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Recalcitrance of APIs and metabolites", "text": "<p>Many API&rsquo;s and their metabolites once excreted from the patient (or in the case of API&rsquo;s discharged into water courses) are recalcitrant to further breakdown, especially in effluent treatment plants/sewage treatment plants (ETP/STP) and natural water courses (rivers, lakes etc.). Considering routes into the environment <em>via</em> the patient, APIs may be excreted unchanged, as mixtures of unchanged API alongside one or several major metabolite(s), or completely metabolised to single or mixtures of metabolite(s).</p>\r\n<p>In the environment, there may be no, partial or full chemical breakdown of the excreted compounds. As with metabolites, breakdown products can be more problematic than the parent compound &ndash; potentially more toxic and more recalcitrant. Many APIs are not removed during typical sewage treatments, but can be absorbed onto sewage sludge.</p>", "remote_id": 588, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 179}, {"fields": {"files": [1333], "lessons": [61], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Decomposition routes", "text": "<p>In the environment, there are four main decomposition routes for API/API metabolite molecules:</p>\r\n<p>1) Chemical</p>\r\n<p>Typically, simple hydrolysis occurring between pH 5 and 8 &ndash;the pH will depend on the exact aquatic environment.</p>\r\n<p>2) Oxidation by air</p>\r\n<p>Most API molecules are resistant to oxidation by air, but maybe oxidised in the presence of catalysts.</p>\r\n<p>3) Enzymatic (or biotic degradation) &ndash; molecules can be absorbed by microorganisms or higher life forms and metabolised <em>via</em> enzyme catalysis. Xenobiotic materials are metabolised to make them more polar to aid excretion, or to begin a breakdown process to utilise the molecule as a carbon/nitrogen source. These enzymatic transformations tend to follow human metabolism pathways &ndash; oxidation, reduction, hydrolysis and other less common transformations. API molecules may encounter enzyme classes (such as p450s - a superfamily of haemoproteins that catalyse the metabolism of a large number of clinically important drugs<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a>) common to humans but with different selectivities, and classes of oxidative enzymes not normally utilized in human metabolism. As with humans, there can also be secondary metabolism &ndash; formation of phosphates, sulphates, and glucuronides. It should be noted that occasionally transformations in the environment can reverse the beneficial metabolic transformations in patients; one of the most problematic API molecules, Ethinyl estradiol (EE2) is partly excreted as the soluble glucuronide which does not have estrogenic and endocrine disruption properties. This is converted back in STPs to the parent API which exhibits these undesirable properties, <strong>Figure 1.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:xx]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 1 Biotic transformations of EE2</strong></p>\r\n<p>4) Photochemical/photochemical oxidation</p>\r\n<p>Direct photolytic decomposition (promotion to an excited state followed by a reaction) requires absorption of natural sunlight by the molecule absorbs (has an absorption maxima &gt;290 nm). If a molecule has a UV/Vis maximum below 290 nm, it may still be decomposed by an indirect photochemical process, through reaction with high energy species like the ROO<sup>.</sup>, OH<sup>.</sup> Radicals and singlet oxygen, which are generated photochemically <em>via</em> dissolved sensitizers based on organic substances like humic acids.</p>\r\n<p>Owing to the stability designed into most pharmaceutical molecules, uncatalysed chemical reactions in the environment may be limited to the hydrolysis of esters and possibly oxidation of highly reactive groups like mercaptans. Chemical transformations will not lead directly to mineralisation, but to a chemical species closely related to the original API which could be resistant to further chemical only transformations. Most APIs are degraded <em>in vivo</em> <em>via</em> enzyme catalysis in microorganisms or <em>in vitro</em> by direct/indirect photochemical pathways.</p>", "remote_id": 589, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 180}, {"fields": {"files": [1324, 1325, 1326, 1327, 1328, 1329, 1330, 1331, 1332, 1334, 1335], "lessons": [62], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Example molecules", "text": "<p>Listed below are 10 typical pharmaceutical molecules and their breakdown products under conditions likely to be encountered in the environment. A number of treatments collectively called advanced oxidation technologies/processes (AOT/AOP) can be used to treat waste water containing chemicals known to be recalcitrant and/or toxic in biological treatment/sewage treatment plants before discharge into the environment. Decomposition products from AOT/AOP processing have not been included since these technologies operate under harsh oxidative conditions that are never encountered in the environment. APIs may come into contact with milder technologies used to disinfect drinking water, which would lead to partial oxidation.</p>\r\n<p>Whatever the mode of reaction, unless a molecule is mineralised, it is ill-advised to assume one or two transformations will render a toxic/recalcitrant molecule less so. Transformation may result in products with greater environmental issues than the original molecule.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a></sup> Likewise, it is unwise to QUANTIFY the eco-toxicity of breakdown products computationally, e.g. with quantitative structure&ndash;activity relationship (QSAR) modelling since:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>It is often inaccurate for the parent pharmaceutical molecules</li>\r\n<li>The assigned structures for the transformation products could be incorrect.</li>\r\n<li>An unambiguous answer can only be reached from physical testing.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The ten molecules have been selected to give examples of APIs across different therapeutic areas and to show examples of biotic, direct and indirect photolytic decomposition. Mainly, primary breakdown products are shown. These could be subject to further degradation processes.</p>\r\n<h3><strong>1) Diclofenac </strong></h3>\r\n<p>[figure:show:295]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 2</strong> <strong>Biotic and photo-degradation routes of diclofenac<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref3\" href=\"#_ftn3\"><strong>[3]</strong></a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref4\" href=\"#_ftn4\"><strong>[4]</strong></a>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref5\" href=\"#_ftn5\"><strong>[5]</strong></a>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref6\" href=\"#_ftn6\"><strong>[6]</strong></a></sup></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>2) Fluoxetine </strong></h3>\r\n<p>[figure:show:296]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 3</strong> <strong>Direct and indirect photo-degrdation of Fluoxetine<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref7\" href=\"#_ftn7\"><strong>[7]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>3) Paroxetine</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:297]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 4 Photo-degradation of paroxetine<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref8\" href=\"#_ftn8\"><strong>[8]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong><strong>[figure:show:298]</strong></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>4) Atorvastin</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:299]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 5 Hydrolysis of Atorvastatin<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref9\" href=\"#_ftn9\"><strong>[9]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>5) Fluphenazine</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:300]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 6</strong> <strong>Photo-degradation of Fluphenazine<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref10\" href=\"#_ftn10\"><strong>[10]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>6) Tamoxifen </strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:301]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:302]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 7</strong> <strong>Photodegradation of Tamoxifen<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref11\" href=\"#_ftn11\"><strong>[11]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>7)&nbsp; Trimethoprim</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:303]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 8 Biotic and photo-degradation of </strong><strong>Trimethoprim</strong><a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref12\" href=\"#_ftn12\">[12]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref13\" href=\"#_ftn13\">[13]</a>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref14\" href=\"#_ftn14\">[14]</a>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref15\" href=\"#_ftn15\">[15]</a></sup></p>\r\n<h3><strong>8) Penicillin G</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:304]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 9 Biotic and chemical breakdown of Penicillin G<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref16\" href=\"#_ftn16\"><strong>[16]</strong></a></strong></p>\r\n<h3><strong>9) Ciproflaxacin</strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:305]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 10</strong> <strong>Photo-degradation of Ciprofloxacin</strong><a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref17\" href=\"#_ftn17\">[17]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref18\" href=\"#_ftn18\">[18]</a></sup></p>\r\n<h3><strong>10) Valsartan </strong></h3>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:306]</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 11 Biotic breakdown of Valsartan<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref19\" href=\"#_ftn19\"><strong>[19]</strong></a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref20\" href=\"#_ftn20\"><strong>[20]</strong></a></sup></strong></p>", "remote_id": 592, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 181}, {"fields": {"files": [1336, 1337, 1338, 1339], "lessons": [63], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Dummy", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 182}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [64], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "The need for environmental risk assessment", "text": "<p>Both the European Medicines Agency (EMA) and the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) require the submission of an environmental risk assessment (ERA) with an application for a marketing license fora new pharmaceutical product. This ERA is based on a defined set of experiments designed to look at the potential effects of the API on three trophic life forms and bacteria, along with other experimentally determined/calculated figures that will give some idea of the <strong>PBT</strong> risk of the API in that pharmaceutical product.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a></p>\r\n<p>Whilst it is mandatory to submit an ERA, no pharmaceutical product has been refused a license on the grounds of an adverse ERA. Although the ERA data to date would suggest most APIs pose negligible risk to the environment. It has been suggested that this is a reflection on the limitations of the current ERA testing protocol.</p>\r\n<p>Typically, approval of a new medicinal product by regulatory authorities is subject to unmet clinical/medical need, efficacy, and safety for the patient. However, the granting of a license for a new API does not automatically mean it will become available, since individual states/regions may decide the cost:benefit ratio is insufficient, and will not reimburse for the product drug.</p>\r\n<p>In certain states, some use is made of ERA data, and there are some who consider that the more widespread use of the ERA data is appropriate.</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Sweden uses ERA data to drive prescribing and reimbursement towards APIs with more favourable environmental profiles.</li>\r\n<li>Some stakeholders would like to see consideration of the ERA part of the marketing authorisation for new pharmaceutical products (see Benign by Design).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The regulatory requirement for an ERA has been in existence since 2006 so for many of the older APIs, no formal ERA data exists although non-regulatory tests may have been performed and published in the open literature.</p>", "remote_id": 609, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 183}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [64], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Description of ERA", "text": "<p>The ERA for an API runs through a number of phases, involving successive levels designed to generate more data if concern around a particular substance increases. These phases are given in <strong>Table 1.</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Table 1</strong> <strong>EMA guidance for Phased ERA<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\"><strong>[1]</strong></a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\"><strong>[2]</strong></a></sup></strong></p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 621px;\" border=\"1\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"130\">\r\n<p><strong>Stage in Regulatory Evaluation</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"134\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Stage in Risk Assessment</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"123\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Objective</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"132\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Method</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"103\">\r\n<p align=\"center\"><strong>Test/Data Requirement</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"130\">\r\n<p><strong>Phase 1</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"134\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Pre-screening</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"123\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Estimation of exposure</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"132\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Action limit</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"103\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Consumption data, log K<sub>ow</sub></p>\r\n<p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"130\">\r\n<p><strong>Phase 2 Tier A</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"134\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Screening</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"123\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Initial prediction of risk</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"132\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Risk Assessment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"103\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Basic set aquatic toxicology and fate</p>\r\n<p align=\"center\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"130\">\r\n<p><strong>Phase 2 Tier B</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"134\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Extended</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"123\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Substance and compartment-specific refinement and risk assessment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"132\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Risk Assessment</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"103\">\r\n<p align=\"center\">Extended data set on emission, fate and effects</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>\r\n<p>The ERA is principally based around two figures: &nbsp;the calculated Predicted Environmental Concentration (PEC) of the API in the environment (water) and the measured concentration at which no adverse environmental issues would be expected (predicted no effect concentration PNEC). ERAs normally provide information on how the PEC/PNEC figures have been calculated. Many ERAs and the data submitted to regulatory agencies are in the public domain and can be found by searching the FDA/EMA websites (examples below). If looking for a specific API, it is always best to search both generic as well as brand names e.g. Rosuvastatin and Crestor.</p>\r\n<p>Sources for ERA data:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>http://www.astrazeneca.com/Responsibility/The-environment/Pharmaceuticals-in-the-environment/era-data-2012.</li>\r\n<li>http://www.msds-gsk.com/</li>\r\n<li>www.fass.se.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<div>&nbsp;</div>", "remote_id": 610, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 184}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [65], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Scope for biodegradable API molecules", "text": "<p>One solution put forward to reducing the burden of PIE is to design and market totally biodegradable API molecules. Vaccines, therapeutic enzymes, hormones and biological therapies (termed &lsquo;biologics&rsquo;) like monoclonal antibodies are not subject to ERA, or to as much scrutiny post patient, as small molecule APIs, as they are deemed to be &lsquo;natural&rsquo; and rapidly breakdown in the patient and environment to form small non-toxic materials like amino acids.</p>\r\n<p>This may not always be the case with &lsquo;hybrid molecules&rsquo; such as PEGylated antibodies and antibody drug conjugates. While the number of biological medicines (biologics) in use has risen over the past 10 years, small molecule APIs are still heavily prevalent for treating many diseases.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> This suggests biologics are unlikely to replace small molecules in the near future and for these small molecules, ERA assessment will still be required (see Regulation and Safety [TODO: link]).</p>", "remote_id": 624, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 185}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [65], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Candidate failure", "text": "<p>Pharmaceutical drug candidates have a failure rate of 93-96% at the R&amp;D stage, as shown in<strong> Figure&nbsp;1</strong>. Early development failure arises from a range of factors such as inadequate pharmacokinetics, bioavailability and unacceptable toxicology profiles, in addition to lack of efficacy in man. Candidate drug properties, a consequence of chemistry design, are key to the success or failure of a proposed molecule.</p>\r\n<p>[show:figure:xx]</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 625, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 186}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [65], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Questions around green design", "text": "<p>One solution to potential PIE issues with new pharmaceuticals is &lsquo;Green Design&rsquo;; the concept of producing drugs with (near) zero environmental impact i.e. one that exhibit no persistence, bioaccumulation or toxicity. This poses a number of questions however:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Could we &lsquo;Design Green&rsquo; without compromise to patient benefit?</li>\r\n<li>Could it apply to all or only some therapies?</li>\r\n<li>Would we want to &lsquo;Design Green&rsquo;? Given the difficulty and large numbers of existing hurdles (Figure 1) in getting new pharmaceuticals to market and hence the patient, why would medicinal chemists add further barriers such as designing molecules for degradation post patient?</li>\r\n<li>When would &lsquo;green benefit&rsquo; emerge?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Developing general guidelines is difficult. Lipinski&rsquo;s famous rule of five describes the desirable &lsquo;drug like&rsquo; properties of a molecule:<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> </p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>No more than 5 hydrogen bond donors.</li>\r\n<li>Not more than 10 hydrogen bond acceptors</li>\r\n<li>A&nbsp;molecular mass less than 500 Da</li>\r\n<li>An octanol/water partition coefficient log <em>P </em>ofno greater than 5</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>At present, a similar guideline for avoiding PBT properties in API molecules does not exist. It is also worth noting that guidelines are not rules &ndash; many successful API molecules do not conform to the Lipinski rule of five. Currently, whether or not an API molecule is PBT, is down to chance, and not a factor of molecular design. A number of strategies to avoid PBT have been put forward for consideration during the molecular design phase, and these will be discussed further.</p>", "remote_id": 626, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 187}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [65], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Example: Glufosfamide", "text": "", "remote_id": 627, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 188}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [64], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Areas of concern", "text": "<p>In the previous section, we outlined the requisite testing in order to assess the likelihood of an API being harmful to the environment. Many pharmaceutical companies carry out and publish studies above and beyond those needed from a regulatory requirement. The regulatory requirement focuses mainly on the fate of the API in the aqueous environment, which is where pharmaceutical residues are most likely destined. Even for aquatic fate, the current ERA testing has its limitations:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Testing APIs for all possible scenarios and all species is not feasible.</li>\r\n<li>Testing is carried out mainly on an API molecule that may pass through the patient unchanged and enter the environment, or be extensively metabolised to other species which are not actually tested [TODO: check this sentence with AW].<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a></li>\r\n<li>Testing looks examines the gross effects and not the non-lethal effects, at the molecular level. One criticism of the current ERA testing is that the tests were designed for looking at acute lethal effects of bulk industrial chemicals, and therefore some of the more subtle non-lethal effects of pharmaceuticals need more sophisticated testing. However, many industrial chemicals show effects like endocrine disruption (alkyl stannanes, Bisphenol A, bis-alkyl phthalates) which are not necessarily addressed by the standard ERA tests.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a>&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Regarding potential human health issues, a number of oestrogenic residues like ethinyl estradiol (EE2) are known to be very toxic, but for most APIs the risk to human health is considered negligible in a high quality drinking water source.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref3\" href=\"#_ftn3\">[3]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref4\" href=\"#_ftn4\">[4]</a>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref5\" href=\"#_ftn5\">[5]</a></sup> The volumes of water needed to consume a single therapeutic dose of APIs present as micro-contaminants are high, as shown in Table 1.Unfortunately, access to high quality, pure drinking water is not a universal human benefit, and serious issues can arise if drinking water sources become contaminated with high levels of APIs.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref6\" href=\"#_ftn6\">[6]</a> Even for EE2, the data suggests that there will only be a risk at high point source concentrations of EE2.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref7\" href=\"#_ftn7\">[7]</a><sup>,<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref8\" href=\"#_ftn8\">[8]</a></sup></p>", "remote_id": 611, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 189}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [64], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Stability testing", "text": "", "remote_id": 612, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 190}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Environmental legislation", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"id\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 191}, {"fields": {"files": [1354], "lessons": [66], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "When it all goes wrong", "text": "", "remote_id": 606, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 192}, {"fields": {"files": [1344], "lessons": [66], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Description of GMP", "text": "", "remote_id": 607, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 193}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "First legislation", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 194}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "DDT: Bhopal", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 195}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Growth in legislation", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 196}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [68], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Current situation", "text": "<p>[AW route selection ppt here]</p>\r\n<p>[TODO: can Andy record a narration for this?]</p>", "remote_id": 617, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 197}, {"fields": {"files": [1336, 1337, 1338, 1339], "lessons": [68], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Concerns and proposed future approaches", "text": "<p>In an ideal situation, an API molecule would be stable during processing and formulation, stable for many years at a range of temperatures and humidities, active and efficacious when taken by the patient; and then be completely metabolised or decomposed in the environment on excretion, into innocuous substances. For more information, see the section on Benign by Design [TODO: link]. In practice, this is very difficult to achieve and represents somewhat of a utopian situation; this is now being recognised by the stakeholders in the pharmaceutical industry. If some APIs can be designed in that way in the future, it would represent an ideal scenario but is very unlikely to be the case for all small molecules.</p>\r\n<p>Additionally of course, it would not solve the issue of the persistence of many of the current treatments, which will continue to be used for the foreseeable future.&nbsp; One obvious course of action to remove human exposure at least, would be to upgrade the water/sewage treatment plants to remove the API residues (or other residues like estrogens). This would come at a cost, Sweden for example, would incur the additional cost of &euro;20\u2011 150 per person per year, for such an upgrade.</p>\r\n<p>Switzerland is one of the first countries to start implementing a national policy to reduce micro pollutants in the effluents of municipal sewage treatment plants and estimates a cost of CHF 86 (US$ 63) per household.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> However, looking at the PIE issues from a patient&rsquo;s perspective, there does not appear to be a great deal of awareness regarding more eco-friendly medicines, nor a willingness to pay more for more environmentally benign medicines<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a> , as shown in <strong>Figure 1</strong>.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:307]<br />[figure:show:308]</p>\r\n<p>Dohle <em>et al</em>. found that&ndash;predictably&ndash; for the patient, the balance between environment and effectiveness was very much driven by the severity of the disease/condition being treated:<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a></p>\r\n<p><em>&lsquo;In the domain of pharmaceuticals used in human medicine, we found that people were willing to consider environmental consequences when choosing a drug, but only when choices were made about treatment options for a rather harmless disease. In contrast, when decisions were made about treatment options for a severe disease, the drug</em><em>&rsquo;</em><em>s effectiveness was the most important criterion. </em><em>Conclusions: </em><em>It can be concluded that the environmental impact of a drug will be hardly considered in decisions about pharmaceuticals for severe diseases like cancer, and this may be due to the fact that these decisions are predominantly affective in nature. However, for less severe health risks, people are willing to balance health and environmental considerations.&rsquo; <br /></em></p>\r\n<p>Looking at stakeholders other than patients, the urgency of the problem and impetus to act increases as you move closer to the industry most likely to be impacted by any legislation for example, in the water industry to remove pollutants like EE2<strong>, Figure 2</strong>.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref2\" href=\"#_ftn2\">[2]</a></p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:309]</p>\r\n<p><strong>Figure 2 Stakeholders perception of PIE</strong></p>\r\n<p>An examination of the various measures to reduce the burden of PIE shows that there is some regional variation on the ranking of various remedies; however correct disposal, development of more eco-friendly products and environmental classification are all close to the top of the lists<sup>4</sup>, as indicated by <strong>Table 1</strong>. As a point of interest, eco-labelling was not deemed a significant measure by those surveyed.<strong> <br /></strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>Table 1 National breakdown of stakeholders options on how to deal with PIE issues</strong></p>\r\n<p><strong>[figure:show:310]</strong></p>", "remote_id": 618, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 198}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [64], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Proposed changes to ERA", "text": "<p>A recent publication by a group of academics from the UK and Sweden has recommended ten changes to the regulatory ERA.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]</a> These are:</p>\r\n<p>1. Require environmental risk assessment also for products put on the market before 2006. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The recommendations were to perform ERA on products retrospectively (i.e. for drugs that were granted a marketing license before the EMA guidelines came into force) to provide relevant information on APIs that could potentially be found in the environment.</p>\r\n<p>2. Add requirements to assess the risk for development of antibiotic resistance</p>\r\n<p>The researchers recommended that the ERA should also include information enabling assessment of the increased risk of antibiotic resistance development to allow for a more accurate representation of the health risks associated with PIE.</p>\r\n<p>3. Perform only one environmental risk assessment per active pharmaceutical ingredient.</p>\r\n<p>It was recommended that only one ERA needed to be performed per API as opposed to each pharmaceutical company having to perform an ERA for the same molecule in order to acheive consistency and reduce the need for duplication of work and animal testing.</p>\r\n<p>4. Refine the tiered approach&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The authors recommended that the tiered approach be refined to include pharmacological, toxicological, and bioconcentration data from the drug discovery process. The result being an improved prioritization process in which ecotoxicity testing can be focused on the most problematic substances and the most relevant test species.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>5. Perform mixture toxicity assessments on active pharmaceutical ingredients with similar modes of action</p>\r\n<p>The recommendation was that the ERA should be carried out on groups of APIs, with similar modes of action to improve accuracy.</p>\r\n<p>6. Mandate use of all available ecotoxicity studies</p>\r\n<p>All reliable and relevant ecotoxicity studies should be included to ensure that all important information was considered, thereby enabling informed decisions.</p>\r\n<p>7. Include environmental risks in the risk-benefit analysis</p>\r\n<p>Inclusion of the environmental risks in the risk-benefit analysis for a candidate was recommended, which would encourage the pharmaceutical companies to perform such assessments on time.</p>\r\n<p>8. Require review of the environmental risk assessments at regular intervals</p>\r\n<p>It was recommended that as new, significant environmental information becomes available, ERAs should be updated accordingly to bring forward regulatory use of new data, which would increase collaboration between stakeholders.</p>\r\n<p>9. Include data from production of active pharmaceutical ingredients and formulations in the environmental risk assessments</p>\r\n<p>API discharges from manufacturing (not just the API itself) should be included in the ERA to cover a wider area of the LCA responsible for the highest environmental concentrations detected.</p>\r\n<p>10. Increase transparency</p>\r\n<p>It was recommended that ERA and manufacturing information be made available to the public domain to both make that information available for the purposes of further reach in this field and provide further incentives for companies to take more environmental responsibility throughout their entire supply chains.</p>", "remote_id": 613, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 6}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 199}, {"fields": {"files": [1413], "lessons": [10], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Example: Sanofi solvent selection guide", "text": "", "remote_id": 620, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 200}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Reducing chance of PBT properties", "text": "<p>A number of suggestions to increase the chances that an API molecule htat will not be persistent have been put forward and &nbsp;include:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Tagging molecules with an affinity marker to allow extraction onto solid supports in Effluent/Sewage Treatment Plants (ETP/STP).</li>\r\n<li>Tagging molecules with functionality known degrade by aerobic/anaerobic bacteria.</li>\r\n<li>Increasing the photosensitivity of molecules to natural sunlight; if the UV maxima is &lt; 290 nm, direct photolysis would not be expected to occur (although indirect photolysis might).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>However none of the above solutions would be practical or desirable as design options in medicinal chemistry. Probably the most practical solutions would be:</p>\r\n<p>1) If possible avoid molecules or fragments known to give rise to environmental problems like PBT.</p>\r\n<p>2) If possible, choose functional groups that are more likely to be biologically degraded</p>\r\n<p>3) Use natural product or natural product like scaffolds</p>\r\n<p>4) Get an early idea of possible PBT issues through screening <em>&ndash; in vivo</em> or <em>in vitro </em>or using animal/human toxicology data to &lsquo;read across&rsquo; to other species.</p>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 201}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Reducing chance of persistence", "text": "<p>A number of suggestions to increase the chances that an API molecule htat will not be persistent have been put forward and &nbsp;include:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Tagging molecules with an affinity marker to allow extraction onto solid supports in Effluent/Sewage Treatment Plants (ETP/STP).</li>\r\n<li>Tagging molecules with functionality known degrade by aerobic/anaerobic bacteria.</li>\r\n<li>Increasing the photosensitivity of molecules to natural sunlight; if the UV maxima is &lt; 290 nm, direct photolysis would not be expected to occur (although indirect photolysis might).</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>However none of the above solutions would be practical or desirable as design options in medicinal chemistry. Probably the most practical solutions would be:</p>\r\n<p>1) If possible avoid molecules or fragments known to give rise to environmental problems like PBT.</p>\r\n<p>2) If possible, choose functional groups that are more likely to be biologically degraded</p>\r\n<p>3) Use natural product or natural product like scaffolds</p>\r\n<p>4) Get an early idea of possible PBT issues through screening <em>&ndash; in vivo</em> or <em>in vitro </em>or using animal/human toxicology data to &lsquo;read across&rsquo; to other species.</p>", "remote_id": 622, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 202}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Avoiding groups likely to give rise to PBT ", "text": "<p>A number of literature sources/published data can show which molecular fragments are more likely to cause PBT issues in molecules that reach the environment.<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"file:///Z:/CHEM21/Education%20and%20Training%20Material/Topic%206/Report%20Breakdown/Chapter%2011_SAS.docx#_msocom_1\"><br /></a></p>\r\n<p>[TODO: need references]</p>", "remote_id": 623, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 203}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Non-functionalised hydrocarbon \u2013 like structures", "text": "<p>(referenced from Lubrizol&rsquo;s Biodegradability Review [6] )</p>\r\n<p>Petroleum hydrocarbons can be divided into 4 classes:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Saturates</li>\r\n<li>Aromatics</li>\r\n<li>Asphaltenes (phenols, fatty acids, ketones, esters and porphyrins)</li>\r\n<li>Resins (pyridines, quinolines, carbazoles, suphoxides and amides)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>These can be sub divided and listed in order of ease of biotic breakdown, so if there is a choice of functionality, the groups with the best chance of biotic breakdown should be used:&nbsp;</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><em>n</em>-alkanes &gt; branched alkanes &gt; low molecular weight aromatics &gt; cyclic alkanes</li>\r\n<li>Saturates &gt; light aromatics &gt; high molecular weight aromatics &gt; polar compounds</li>\r\n<li>Electron-rich aromatics&gt;aromatics with electron withdrawing groups &gt;heterocycles</li>\r\n<li>Substituted aromatics ortho&gt; para&gt; meta</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 629, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 204}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Functionalised molecules", "text": "<p>Scheringer <em>et al</em>. examined ~95,000 compounds for PBT properties with the thresholds defined under REACH.<a title=\"\" name=\"_ftnref1\" href=\"file:///Z:/CHEM21/Education%20and%20Training%20Material/Topic%206/Report%20Breakdown/Chapter%2011_SAS.docx#_ftn1\">[1]</a> Some data was experimental but most was obtained by modelling (QSAR). Depending on which data set the chemicals were taken from, between 3-5% of the total were classified as potentially PBT. The most common structural motifs noted in the PBT set are listed below alongside a comparison with common functionality found in pharmaceutical molecules. Two or more of these structural elements are frequently found in the PBT hazard class of chemicals identified.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:xx]</p>\r\n<p>It can be seen from the above analysis, that some motifs with high alert for PBT are never or rarely seen in APIs, but some are very common like aliphatic branched amines and ethers.&nbsp; Generally, if there is a choice, in the case of amines, ethers and alcohols, the biotic degradation will favour: primary &gt;secondary &gt;tertiary, and steric hindrance and branching around heteroatom centres are liable to greatly reduce the rates of breakdown. Spiro compounds are also worthy of note, whilst they are not common in API molecules at present, there is a growing interest in using more spiro fragments and as such spiro compounds may therefore become more prevalent in the future. &nbsp;&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 630, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 205}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Fluorination", "text": "<p>Another major area for consideration is fluorination; Looking at the percentage of halogens s introduced into aromatic rings during API synthesis in <strong>Figure 4</strong>, nearly all fluorine and some chlorine are retained in the final API molecule. Traditionally, all bromine and iodine that is introduced, is later removed in the synthesis; as these elements are only used as a synthetic handles&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>[show:figure:xx]</p>\r\n<p>This picture is beginning to change somewhat, with a few more brominated and iodinated aryl APIs being launched. Generally biotic degradation follows the trend: &nbsp;I&gt;Br&gt;Cl&gt; F, with organoiodides also being prone to photo-degradation. Fluorinated compounds are very common,most 15-30% of API portfolios consisting of fluorinated molecules. Fluorine is often chosen for the specific beneficial properties it lends to API molecules, and is unlikely to disappear from small molecule API portfolios in the near future, if ever. Of course, there is some degree of variation year on year, but the overall trend seems to be increasing the mix of aliphatic C-F and CF<sub>3 </sub>&nbsp;units alongside the more traditional sp<sup>2</sup> C-F aryl and heteroaryl fluorides, as shown in<strong>Figure 5</strong>. Typically organofluorine compounds are resistant to biotic breakdown, and polyfluorination leads to highly hydrophobic molecules that have a tendency to bioaccumulate. CF<sub>3</sub>-containing molecules may generate the persistent molecule CF<sub>3</sub>CO<sub>2</sub>H if mineralisation occurs.</p>\r\n<p>Despite this, it remains fairly inconceivable that small molecule drugs will be produced in the future without fluorine, tertiary amines, heterocycles etc.</p>\r\n<p>[figure:show:xx]</p>", "remote_id": 631, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 206}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Summary", "text": "<p>To summarise, some steps that can be taken to minimise PBT issues with candidate drugs are listed below:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Avoid polyhalogenated fragments (F, Cl, &nbsp;Br).</li>\r\n<li>Avoid fluorine if at all possible.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid large numbers of fused aromatic rings.</li>\r\n<li>If possible the use of aliphatic rings is preferable to benzene/heteroaromatic rings .</li>\r\n<li>Highly substituted aromatic rings can be problematic.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid highly branched aliphatics.</li>\r\n<li>Avoid highly hindered/quaternary carbons if possible.</li>\r\n<li>Spiro compounds &ndash; be alert.</li>\r\n<li>Esters are preferable to amides</li>\r\n<li>Amides primary&gt;secondary&gt;tertiary</li>\r\n<li>Ureas are preferable to sulphonamides</li>\r\n<li>High aqueous solubility</li>\r\n<li>As low K<sub>ow</sub> as feasible</li>\r\n<li>Aim for as low a molecular weight as possible</li>\r\n<li>Positive if the compound has a UV/Vis maxima &gt; 290 nM</li>\r\n<li>Use ecotoxicity testing earlier on in the development pipeline to highlight potential environmental issues.</li>\r\n<li>Use predictive tools but understand their limitations &ndash;probably quite good for P and B &ndash; not reliable for T (for quantitative measures of ecotoxicity) &ndash; some links are provided below.</li>\r\n<li>Look for structural similarity with compounds known to have PBT issues</li>\r\n<li>Look for plausible degradation pathways that lead to known PBT fragments.</li>\r\n<li>Make use of &ldquo;read across&rdquo; data but understand the associated risks and limitations.</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 632, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 6}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 207}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [70], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Predictive tools", "text": "<p>A selection of predictive tools are listed below. Some are collections or suites of publically available tools. The tools listed below are representative and not a comprehensive list of what is available</p>\r\n<p><strong>ECOSAR</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/oppt/newchems/tools/21ecosar.htm\">http://www.epa.gov/oppt/newchems/tools/21ecosar.htm</a></p>\r\n<p>The Ecological Structure Activity Relationships (ECOSAR) class program is a predictive software program system that estimates aquatic toxicity.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>EPA Sustainable Futures</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/oppt/sf/\">http://www.epa.gov/oppt/sf/</a></p>\r\n<p>A suite of links to free tools and training materials</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/oppt/sf/pubs/index.htm#case\">http://www.epa.gov/oppt/sf/pubs/index.htm#case</a></p>\r\n<p>Published data and examples</p>\r\n<p><strong>Estimation Program Interface (EPI) Suite</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.epa.gov/opptintr/exposure/pubs/episuite.htm\">http://www.epa.gov/opptintr/exposure/pubs/episuite.htm</a></p>\r\n<p>The EPI (Estimation Programs Interface) Suite&trade; is a suite of physical/chemical property and environmental fate estimation programs &ndash; basically a single interface to a wide range of publically available tools.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Persistent, Bioaccumulative, and Toxic Profiles Estimated for Organic Chemicals</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://www.pbtprofiler.net/\">http://www.pbtprofiler.net/</a></p>\r\n<p><strong>ETH Biocatalysis / biodegradation database</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://eawag-bbd.ethz.ch/predict/index.html\">http://eawag-bbd.ethz.ch/predict/index.html</a></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Predicts biotic (aerobic and anaerobic) decomposition pathways.</span></p>\r\n<p>Of course, many commercial modelling packages can be accessed if desired.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">http://www.simulations-plus.com/Products.aspx?pID=13</span></p>", "remote_id": 633, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 8}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 208}, {"fields": {"files": [1415], "lessons": [71], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video 1", "text": "<p>In this video the difference in demands for results affects the requirements for those results, e.g. a research chemist may only need a few mg of a substance to prove the ability to make a compound whereas a process chemist needs several kg or tonnes to be able to sell which therefore affects the planning of the whole synthetic route. </p>", "remote_id": 636, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 209}, {"fields": {"files": [1417], "lessons": [71], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video 2", "text": "<p>This video explains in more depth the different types of data and information required from the medicinal and process chemists.&nbsp; </p>", "remote_id": 637, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 210}, {"fields": {"files": [1418], "lessons": [72], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video 1", "text": "<p>This video explains how both medicinal and process chemists contribute at each stage of the development of a new API.</p>", "remote_id": 639, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 211}, {"fields": {"files": [1051], "lessons": [72], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video 2", "text": "<p>Now that we have have had an overview of the API development route, this video now explains how this route typically plays out in practice. </p>", "remote_id": 640, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 212}, {"fields": {"files": [1049], "lessons": [73], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video 1", "text": "<p>In this video, estradiol is used as a case study to illustrate the transition of methodology from research to process chemistry</p>", "remote_id": 642, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 213}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Summary", "text": "", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 214}, {"fields": {"files": [1052], "lessons": [74], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video 1", "text": "<p>This video presents a summary of the material covered in this module.</p>\r\n<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\r\n  <o:AllowPNG/>\r\n </o:OfficeDocumentSettings>\r\n</xml><![endif]-->\r\n<p class=\"MsoListParagraph\" style=\"text-indent: -18.0pt; mso-list: l0 level1 lfo1;\"><span style=\"mso-bidi-font-family: Calibri; mso-bidi-theme-font: minor-latin;\"><span style=\"mso-list: Ignore;\">1.<span style=\"font: 7.0pt 'Times New Roman';\">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></span></span>This video presents a summary of the material covered in this module.</p>\r\n<!--[if gte mso 9]><xml>\r\n <w:WordDocument>\r\n  <w:View>Normal</w:View>\r\n  <w:Zoom>0</w:Zoom>\r\n  <w:TrackMoves/>\r\n  <w:TrackFormatting/>\r\n  <w:PunctuationKerning/>\r\n  <w:ValidateAgainstSchemas/>\r\n  <w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>false</w:SaveIfXMLInvalid>\r\n  <w:IgnoreMixedContent>false</w:IgnoreMixedContent>\r