 other bond formations", "text": "", "remote_id": 687, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 5}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 249}, {"fields": {"files": [1064], "lessons": [16], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Video", "text": "", "remote_id": 676, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 0}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 250}, {"fields": {"files": [1420], "lessons": [], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvents in industry", "text": "<p>Solvents are liquids that are capable of dissolving or dispersing other substances.&nbsp; They are used in very high volumes in industry: in the following video Chris Rayner talks through some of their industrial uses, and the issues around them.&nbsp; From a number of cradle-to-gate lifecycle studies it is generally recognised that the major contributor to the lifecycle impacts of API synthesis is due to solvents.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p class=\"Default\">From a green chemistry point of view, solvents therefore become an area where greatest impact can be achieved by reducing the amount of solvent waste, and minimising human and environmental consequences through the choice and volumes of solvent used.&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": null, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"type\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\", \"id\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 251}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [22], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Common solvent classes", "text": "<p>Some common classes of solvents:</p>\r\n<table style=\"width: 350px;\" border=\"0\" cellspacing=\"0\" cellpadding=\"0\">\r\n<tbody>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p><strong>Solvent Class</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p><strong>Example</strong></p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Alkanes</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Hexane</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Aromatics</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Toluene</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Alcohols</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Ethanol</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Ethers</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Diethyl ether</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Polar aprotic</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Acetonitrile</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Chlorinated</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Dichloromethane</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Ketones</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Acetone</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Acids</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Acetic acid</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n<tr>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"170\">\r\n<p>Bases</p>\r\n</td>\r\n<td valign=\"top\" width=\"180\">\r\n<p>Pyridine</p>\r\n</td>\r\n</tr>\r\n</tbody>\r\n</table>", "remote_id": 702, "dirty": "[\"h5p_library\", \"h5p_resources\", \"json_content\"]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 252}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [22], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Why organic solvents? ", "text": "<p>There are various reasons for using organic solvents:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Mixing (mass transport/phases)</li>\r\n<li>Selectivity</li>\r\n<li>Reaction rate</li>\r\n<li>Scalability</li>\r\n<li>Safety &ndash; (exotherm control)</li>\r\n<li>Isolation</li>\r\n<li>Cleaning</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 703, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 253}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [85], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvents of concern", "text": "<p>At the screening level, as broad a range of solvents as possible will be utilised to determine ideal conditions such as solubility, reaction temperature (as determined by boiling point), partition coefficient <em>etc</em>. (C. R. McElroy, A. Constantinou, L. C. Jones, L. Summerton, J. H. Clark,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2015, <strong>17</strong>, 3111)&nbsp; The use of a full solvent set will indicate which classes of solubilising agents give best results and what solvent properties dominate the solvent effects.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>However researchers should be aware of solvents that have been categorised as highly hazardous or worse and their use should be avoided even during screening reactions.&nbsp; The highly hazardous classifications can be due to health, safety or environmental reasons as well as regulatory constraints.&nbsp; In <a href=\"http://pubs.acs.org/paragonplus/submission/oprdfk/oprdfk_scope.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">their editorial policy</a>, the journal Organic Process Research and Development discourages research conducted using &lsquo;strongly undesirable solvents&rsquo; such as benzene, carbon tetrachloride, chloroform, HMPA, carbon disulphide.</p>\r\n<p>Solvents that fall into this category include (D. Prat, J. Hayler, A. Wells,<em> Green Chem.</em>, 2014, <strong>16</strong>, 4546)):</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Carcinogenic solvents e.g. benzene, 1,2-dichloroethane (H350).</li>\r\n<li>Ozone depleting solvents e.g. Carbon tetrachloride (H420).</li>\r\n<li>Chloroform, due to its toxicity.</li>\r\n<li>Diethyl ether, due to the safety risks associated with its low flash point; low boiling point; resistivity; ability to form peroxides and low auto-ignition temperature.</li>\r\n<li>Nitromethane, due to its high energy of decomposition.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Dipolar aprotic solvents are another class of solvents that are subject to an increasing amount of scrutiny.&nbsp; N,N-dimethylformamide (DMF), N,N-dimethylacetamide (DMAc) and 1-Methyl-2-pyrrolidone (NMP) have all been named as substances of very high concern (SVHC) on <a href=\"http://echa.europa.eu/candidate-list-table\">the REACH Candidate list for Authorisation</a></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>", "remote_id": 691, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 254}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [85], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Other issues", "text": "<ul>\r\n<li>Process safety</li>\r\n<li>Worker safety and health</li>\r\n<li>Regulatory guidelines &ndash; Patient safety</li>\r\n<li>Corporate Responsibility &ndash; drive for sustainable manufacture</li>\r\n<li>Disposal</li>\r\n<li>Environmental Impact of VOCs\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Harmful effects on\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>human health e.g. 1,2-Dichloroethane and DMF</li>\r\n<li>natural ecosystems e.g. Hexanes</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n<li>Damage to materials e.g. acids</li>\r\n<li>Tropospheric photochemical oxidant formation e.g. Xylene, Toluene</li>\r\n<li>Stratospheric ozone depletion e.g. carbon tetrachloride, methyl bromide, Freon 22</li>\r\n<li>Global Climate change</li>\r\n<li>Odour e.g. amines &ndash; pyridine, triethylamine, DMS</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 692, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 255}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [86], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Industrial Emissions Directive, Water Framework Directive (WFD)", "text": "<p><a href=\"http://ec.europa.eu/environment/water/water-framework/index_en.html\">The WFD</a> seeks to <strong>constantly improve the quality </strong>of inland and coastal waters by <strong>severely restricting </strong>compounds such as dichloromethane or totally phasing out (by 2025) compounds like Hg. Environmental Quality Standard (EQS) for dichloromethane has been set to 20&mu;g litre<sup>-1</sup>. Any discharge contributing &gt;1% of this level is likely to be scrutinised by the regulatory agency, hence the remediation of aqueous waste streams contaminated with dichloromethane will be difficult and costly.</p>", "remote_id": 694, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 256}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [86], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvent Emissions Directive (SED) ", "text": "<p><a href=\"ttp://rod.eionet.europa.eu/instruments/536\">The SED</a> seeks to <strong>limit the discharge </strong>of VOCs to the environment. Also, the directive seeks to <strong>replace</strong> the most harmful VOCs.&nbsp; The use of these solvents is still possible <strong>with justification</strong>, but <strong>very tight emission limits</strong> apply.</p>", "remote_id": 695, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 257}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [86], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "REACH", "text": "<p><a href=\"http://ec.europa.eu/environment/chemicals/reach/reach_en.htm\">REACH (Registration, Evaluation, Authorisation and Restriction of Chemicals)</a> is the European legislation for control of chemicals. It specifies which chemicals must be registered and how; how to evaluate chemical substances and how to restrict access to chemicals that are regarded as especially dangerous for human health or the environment.</p>", "remote_id": 697, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 4}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 258}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [86], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Montreal Protocol", "text": "<p><a href=\"http://ozone.unep.org/en/treaties-and-decisions/montreal-protocol-substances-deplete-ozone-layer\">The Montreal Protocol</a> was designed to eliminate substances that deplete ozone by reaction with ozone (O<sub>3</sub>) in the stratosphere</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs) and Halons</li>\r\n<li>Hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs) e.g. R22</li>\r\n<li>Hydrobromofluorocarbons (HBFCs)</li>\r\n<li>Carbon tetrachloride</li>\r\n<li>Methyl chloroform (1,1,1-trichloroethane)</li>\r\n<li>Methyl bromide</li>\r\n<li>Bromochloromethane</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 696, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 3}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 259}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [87], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Considerations for solvent selection", "text": "<p>Frequently a solvent is chosen for a particular reaction due to literature precedent or in-house routine practice.&nbsp; However a more strategic approach should take into consideration the following:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Inert under reaction conditions</li>\r\n<li>Chemistry must work!</li>\r\n<li>Isolation/work-up/crystallisation</li>\r\n<li>Safety and operability</li>\r\n<li>Human health issues</li>\r\n<li>Can the solvent be recovered/recycled?</li>\r\n<li>Can wastes be incinerated/treated?</li>\r\n<li>Environment and legislation compliance</li>\r\n<li>Overall cost burden to final product</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 700, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 2}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 260}, {"fields": {"files": [], "lessons": [87], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "What could be greener alternatives?", "text": "<p>What could be greener alternatives?</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Neat &ndash; no solvent!</li>\r\n<li>Solid phase reactions</li>\r\n<li>Water</li>\r\n<li>Bio-derived solvents</li>\r\n<li>Compressed gases</li>\r\n<li>Supercritical fluids</li>\r\n<li>Ionic liquids [TODO:link to topic 3]<a id=\"_anchor_1\" name=\"_msoanchor_1\" href=\"#_msocom_1\"><br /></a></li>\r\n<li>Seek substitutes from Solvent Selection Guides [TODO: link to topic 2]</li>\r\n</ul>", "remote_id": 699, "dirty": "[]", "pdf": null, "order": 1}, "model": "repo.question", "pk": 261}, {"fields": {"files": [1420], "lessons": [22], "order_dirty": true, "byline": "", "title": "Solvents in industry", "text": "<p>Solvents are liquids that are capable of dissolving or dispersing other substances.&nbsp; They are used in very high volumes in industry: in the video below Chris Rayner outlines various industrial uses and the issues around them.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Fro